# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: work-output
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:work-output/compound-machine] A **simple machine** is a mechanical device that changes the direction or magnitude of a force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] In general, they can be defined as the simplest mechanisms that use mechanical advantage (also called leverage) to multiply force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] A simple machine uses a single applied force to do work against a single load force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Ignoring friction losses, the work done on the load is equal to the work done by the applied force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] A machine can therefore increase the amount of the output force, at the cost of a proportional decrease in the distance moved by the load.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The ratio of the output to the applied force is called the *mechanical advantage*.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Simple machines can be regarded as elementary "building blocks" of which more complicated machines (sometimes called "compound machines") are composed.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] For example, wheels, levers, and pulleys are all used in the mechanism of a bicycle.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The mechanical advantage of a compound machine can be determined as the product of the mechanical advantages contained in the simple machines of which it is composed.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The proliferation and sophistication of modern machine linkages, intensified during the Industrial Revolution, is inadequately described by these six simple categories.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Various post-Renaissance authors have compiled expanded lists of "simple machines", often using terms like *basic machines*, *compound machines*, or *machine elements* to distinguish them from the classical simple machines above.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] By the late 1800s, Franz Reuleaux had identified hundreds of machine elements, calling them *simple machines*.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Modern machine theory analyzes machines as kinematic chains composed of elementary linkages called kinematic pairs.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The idea of a simple machine originated with the Greek philosopher Archimedes around the 3rd century BC, who studied the Archimedean simple machines: lever, pulley, and screw.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] He discovered the principle of mechanical advantage in the lever.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Archimedes' famous remark with regard to the lever: "Give me a place to stand on, and I will move the Earth," (Greek: δῶς μοι πᾶ στῶ καὶ τὰν γᾶν κινάσω) expresses his realization that there was no limit to the degree of force amplification that could be achieved by using mechanical advantage.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Later Greek philosophers defined the classic five simple machines (excluding the inclined plane) and were able to calculate their (ideal) mechanical advantage.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] 10–75 AD) in his work *Mechanics* lists five mechanisms that can "set a load in motion": lever, windlass, pulley, wedge, and screw, and describes their fabrication and uses.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] However the Greeks' understanding was limited to the statics of simple machines (the balance of forces), and did not include dynamics, the tradeoff between force and distance, or the concept of work.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] During the Renaissance the dynamics of the *mechanical powers*, as the simple machines were called, began to be studied from the standpoint of how far they could lift a load, in addition to the force they could apply, leading eventually to the new concept of mechanical work.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] In 1586 Flemish engineer Simon Stevin derived the mechanical advantage of the inclined plane, and it was included with the other simple machines.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The complete dynamic theory of simple machines was worked out by Italian scientist Galileo Galilei in 1600 in *Le Mecaniche* (*On Mechanics*), in which he showed the underlying mathematical similarity of the machines as force amplifiers.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] He was the first to explain that simple machines do not create energy, only transform it.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The classic rules of sliding friction in machines were discovered by Leonardo da Vinci (1452–1519), but were unpublished and merely documented in his notebooks, and were based on pre-Newtonian science such as believing friction was an ethereal fluid.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] They were rediscovered by Guillaume Amontons (1699) and were further developed by Charles-Augustin de Coulomb (1785).
[src:work-output/compound-machine] If a simple machine does not dissipate energy through friction, wear or deformation, then energy is conserved and it is called an ideal simple machine.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] In this case, the power into the machine equals the power out, and the mechanical advantage can be calculated from its geometric dimensions.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Although each machine works differently mechanically, the way they function is similar mathematically.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] In each machine, a force $F_{\text{in}}$ is applied to the device at one point, and it does work moving a load $F_{\text{out}}$ at another point.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] that can be calculated from the machine's geometry and friction.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Simple machines do not contain a source of energy, so they cannot do more work than they receive from the input force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] A simple machine with no friction or elasticity is called an *ideal machine*.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The power output equals the velocity of the load $v_{\text{out}}\,$ multiplied by the load force $P_{\text{out}}=F_{\text{out}}v_{\text{out}}\,$ .
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Similarly the power input from the applied force is equal to the velocity of the input point $v_{\text{in}}\,$ multiplied by the applied force $P_{\text{in}}=F_{\text{in}}v_{\text{in}}\!$ .
[src:work-output/compound-machine] This can be calculated from the geometry of the machine.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] For example, the mechanical advantage and distance ratio of the lever is equal to the ratio of its lever arms.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] In the screw, which uses rotational motion, the input force should be replaced by the torque, and the velocity by the angular velocity the shaft is turned.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] All real machines have friction, which causes some of the input power to be dissipated as heat.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] So in non-ideal machines, the mechanical advantage is always less than the velocity ratio by the product with the efficiency $\eta$ .
[src:work-output/compound-machine] So a machine that includes friction will not be able to move as large a load as a corresponding ideal machine using the same input force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] A *compound machine* is a machine formed from a set of simple machines connected in series with the output force of one providing the input force to the next.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] For example, a bench vise consists of a lever (the vise's handle) in series with a screw, and a simple gear train consists of a number of gears (wheels and axles) connected in series.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] In many simple machines, if the load force $F_{\textrm {out}}$ on the machine is high enough in relation to the input force $F_{\textrm {in}}$ , the machine will move backwards, with the load force doing work on the input force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] So these machines can be used in either direction, with the driving force applied to either input point.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] For example, if the load force on a lever is high enough, the lever will move backwards, moving the input arm backwards against the input force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] These are called *reversible*, *non-locking* or *overhauling* machines, and the backward motion is called *overhauling*.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] However, in some machines, if the frictional forces are high enough, no amount of load force can move it backwards, even if the input force is zero.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] This is called a *self-locking*, *nonreversible*, or *non-overhauling* machine.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] These machines can only be set in motion by a force at the input, and when the input force is removed will remain motionless, "locked" by friction at whatever position they were left.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Whether a machine is self-locking depends on both the friction forces (coefficient of static friction) between its parts, and the distance ratio $d_{\textrm {in}}/d_{\textrm {out}}$ (ideal mechanical advantage).
[src:work-output/compound-machine] If both the friction and ideal mechanical advantage are high enough, it will self-lock.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Thus the machine self-locks, because the work dissipated in friction is greater than the work done by the load force moving it backwards even with no input force.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Machines are studied as mechanical systems consisting of actuators and mechanisms that transmit forces and movement, monitored by sensors and controllers.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The components of actuators and mechanisms consist of links and joints that form kinematic chains.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Simple machines are elementary examples of kinematic chains that are used to model mechanical systems ranging from the steam engine to robot manipulators.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The bearings that form the fulcrum of a lever and that allow the wheel and axle and pulleys to rotate are examples of a kinematic pair called a hinged joint.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Similarly, the flat surface of an inclined plane and wedge are examples of the kinematic pair called a sliding joint.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The screw is usually identified as its own kinematic pair called a helical joint.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Two levers, or cranks, are combined into a planar four-bar linkage by attaching a link that connects the output of one crank to the input of another.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Additional links can be attached to form a six-bar linkage or in series to form a robot.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The identification of simple machines arises from a desire for a systematic method to invent new machines.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Therefore, an important concern is how simple machines are combined to make more complex machines.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] One approach is to attach simple machines in series to obtain compound machines.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] However, a more successful strategy was identified by Franz Reuleaux, who collected and studied over 800 elementary machines.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] He realized that a lever, pulley, and wheel and axle are in essence the same device: a body rotating about a hinge.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Similarly, an inclined plane, wedge, and screw are a block sliding on a flat surface.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] This realization shows that it is the joints, or the connections that provide movement, that are the primary elements of a machine.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] Starting with four types of joints, the revolute joint, sliding joint, cam joint and gear joint, and related connections such as cables and belts, it is possible to understand a machine as an assembly of solid parts that connect these joints.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] The design of mechanisms to perform required movement and force transmission is known as kinematic synthesis.
[src:work-output/compound-machine] This is a collection of geometric techniques for the mechanical design of linkages, cam and follower mechanisms and gears and gear trains.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Energy conversion efficiency depends on the usefulness of the output.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] All or part of the heat produced from burning a fuel may become rejected waste heat if, for example, work is the desired output from a thermodynamic cycle.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Energy converter is an example of an energy transformation.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] For example, a light bulb falls into the categories energy converter. $\eta ={\frac {P_{\mathrm {out} }}{P_{\mathrm {in} }}}$ Even though the definition includes the notion of usefulness, efficiency is considered a technical or physical term.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Goal or mission oriented terms include effectiveness and efficacy.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Generally, energy conversion efficiency is a dimensionless number between 0 and 1.0, or 0% to 100%.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Efficiencies cannot exceed 100%, which would result in a perpetual motion machine, which is impossible.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] However, other effectiveness measures that can exceed 1.0 are used for refrigerators, heat pumps and other devices that move heat rather than convert it.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] It is not called efficiency, but the coefficient of performance, or COP.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] It is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided relative to the work (energy) required.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Higher COPs equate to higher efficiency, lower energy (power) consumption and thus lower operating costs.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The COP usually exceeds 1, especially in heat pumps, because instead of just converting work to heat (which, if 100% efficient, would be a COP of 1), it pumps additional heat from a heat source to where the heat is required.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Most air conditioners have a COP of 2.3 to 3.5.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] When talking about the efficiency of heat engines and power stations the convention should be stated, i.e., HHV (a.k.a.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Gross Heating Value, etc.) or LCV (a.k.a.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Net Heating value), and whether gross output (at the generator terminals) or net output (at the power station fence) are being considered.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The two are separate but both must be stated.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Failure to do so causes endless confusion.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The energy efficiency of a process involving chemical change may be expressed relative to these theoretical minima or maxima.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The difference between the change of enthalpy and the change of Gibbs energy of a chemical transformation at a particular temperature indicates the heat input required or the heat removal (cooling) required to maintain that temperature.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] A fuel cell may be considered to be the reverse of electrolysis.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] It would operate at a cell voltage of 1.24 V.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] For a water electrolysis unit operating at a constant temperature of 25 °C without the input of any additional heat energy, electrical energy would have to be supplied at a rate equivalent of the enthalpy (heat) of reaction or 285.830 kJ (0.07940 kWh) per gram mol of water consumed.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] It would operate at a cell voltage of 1.48 V.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The electrical energy input of this cell is 1.20 times greater than the theoretical minimum so the energy efficiency is 0.83 compared to the ideal cell.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] A water electrolysis unit operating with a higher voltage that 1.48 V and at a temperature of 25 °C would have to have heat energy removed in order to maintain a constant temperature and the energy efficiency would be less than 0.83.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The large entropy difference between liquid water and gaseous hydrogen plus gaseous oxygen accounts for the significant difference between the Gibbs energy of reaction and the enthalpy (heat) of reaction.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Using the LHV, a condensing boiler can achieve a "heating efficiency" in excess of 100% (this does not violate the first law of thermodynamics as long as the LHV convention is understood, but does cause confusion).
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] This is because the apparatus recovers part of the heat of vaporization, which is not included in the definition of the lower heating value of a fuel.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] In the U.S. and elsewhere, the **higher heating value** (HHV) is used, which includes the latent heat for condensing the water vapor, and thus the thermodynamic maximum of 100% efficiency cannot be exceeded.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] In optical systems such as lighting and lasers, the energy conversion efficiency is often referred to as wall-plug efficiency.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The wall-plug efficiency is the measure of output radiative-energy, in watts (joules per second), per total input electrical energy in watts.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The output energy is usually measured in terms of absolute irradiance and the wall-plug efficiency is given as a percentage of the total input energy, with the inverse percentage representing the losses.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Instead of using watts, the power of a light source to produce wavelengths proportional to human perception is measured in lumens.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The human eye is most sensitive to wavelengths of 555 nanometers (greenish-yellow) but the sensitivity decreases dramatically to either side of this wavelength, following a Gaussian power-curve and dropping to zero sensitivity at the red and violet ends of the spectrum.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Due to this the eye does not usually see all of the wavelengths emitted by a particular light-source, nor does it see all of the wavelengths within the visual spectrum equally.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Therefore, the radiant intensity of a light source may be much greater than its luminous intensity, meaning that the source emits more energy than the eye can use.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Likewise, the lamp's wall-plug efficiency is usually greater than its luminous efficiency.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The effectiveness of a light source to convert electrical energy into wavelengths of visible light, in proportion to the sensitivity of the human eye, is referred to as luminous efficacy, which is measured in units of lumens per watt (lm/w) of electrical input-energy.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Unlike efficacy (effectiveness), which is a unit of measurement, efficiency is a unitless number expressed as a percentage, requiring only that the input and output units be of the same type.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The luminous efficiency of a light source is thus the percentage of luminous efficacy per theoretical maximum efficacy at a specific wavelength.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The amount of energy carried by a photon of light is determined by its wavelength.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] In lumens, this energy is offset by the eye's sensitivity to the selected wavelengths.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] For example, a green laser pointer can have greater than 30 times the apparent brightness of a red pointer of the same power output.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] At 555 nm in wavelength, 1 watt of radiant energy is equivalent to 683 lumens, thus a monochromatic light source at this wavelength, with a luminous efficacy of 683 lm/w, would have a luminous efficiency of 100%.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The theoretical-maximum efficacy lowers for wavelengths at either side of 555 nm.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] For example, low-pressure sodium lamps produce monochromatic light at 589 nm with a luminous efficacy of 200 lm/w, which is the highest of any lamp.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The theoretical-maximum efficacy at that wavelength is 525 lm/w, so the lamp has a luminous efficiency of 38.1%.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Because the lamp is monochromatic, the luminous efficiency nearly matches the wall-plug efficiency of < 40%.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Calculations for luminous efficiency become more complex for lamps that produce white light or a mixture of spectral lines.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Fluorescent lamps have higher wall-plug efficiencies than low-pressure sodium lamps, but only have half the luminous efficacy of ~ 100 lm/w, thus the luminous efficiency of fluorescents is lower than sodium lamps.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] A xenon flashtube has a typical wall-plug efficiency of 50–70%, exceeding that of most other forms of lighting.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Because the flashtube emits large amounts of infrared and ultraviolet radiation, only a portion of the output energy is used by the eye.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The luminous efficacy is therefore typically around 50 lm/w.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] However, not all applications for lighting involve the human eye nor are restricted to visible wavelengths.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] For laser pumping, the efficacy is not related to the human eye so it is not called "luminous" efficacy, but rather simply "efficacy" as it relates to the absorption lines of the laser medium.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Krypton flashtubes are often chosen for pumping Nd:YAG lasers, even though their wall-plug efficiency is typically only ~ 40%.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Krypton's spectral lines better match the absorption lines of the neodymium-doped crystal, thus the efficacy of krypton for this purpose is much higher than xenon; able to produce up to twice the laser output for the same electrical input.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] All of these terms refer to the amount of energy and lumens as they exit the light source, disregarding any losses that might occur within the lighting fixture or subsequent output optics.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] *Luminaire efficiency* refers to the total lumen-output from the fixture per the lamp output.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Low-pressure sodium lamps initially convert the electrical energy using an electrical ballast, to maintain the proper current and voltage, but some energy is lost in the ballast.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Similarly, fluorescent lamps also convert the electricity using a ballast (electronic efficiency).
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The electricity is then converted into light energy by the electrical arc (electrode efficiency and discharge efficiency).
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The light is then transferred to a fluorescent coating that only absorbs suitable wavelengths, with some losses of those wavelengths due to reflection off and transmission through the coating (transfer efficiency).
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The number of photons absorbed by the coating will not match the number then reemitted as fluorescence (quantum efficiency).
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] Finally, due to the phenomenon of the Stokes shift, the re-emitted photons will have a longer wavelength (thus lower energy) than the absorbed photons (fluorescence efficiency).
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] In very similar fashion, lasers also experience many stages of conversion between the wall plug and the output aperture.
[src:work-output/energy-conversion-efficiency] The terms "wall-plug efficiency" or "energy conversion efficiency" are therefore used to denote the overall efficiency of the energy-conversion device, deducting the losses from each stage, although this may exclude external components needed to operate some devices, such as coolant pumps.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In physics, a **force** is an action that can cause an object to change its velocity or its shape, or to resist other forces, or to cause changes of pressure in a fluid.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In mechanics, force makes ideas like *pushing* or *pulling* mathematically precise.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Because the magnitude and direction of a force are both important, force is a vector quantity (**force vector**).
[src:work-output/force-p01] The SI unit of force is the newton (N), and force is often represented by the symbol **F**.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Force plays an important role in classical mechanics.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The concept of force is central to all three of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Types of forces often encountered in classical mechanics include elastic, frictional, contact or "normal" forces, and gravitational.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The rotational version of force is torque, which produces changes in the rotational speed of an object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In an extended body, each part applies forces on the adjacent parts; the distribution of such forces through the body is the internal mechanical stress.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In the case of multiple forces, if the net force on an extended body is zero the body is in equilibrium.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In modern physics, which includes relativity and quantum mechanics, the laws governing motion are revised to rely on fundamental interactions as the ultimate origin of force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] However, the understanding of force provided by classical mechanics is useful for practical purposes.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Philosophers in antiquity used the concept of force in the study of stationary and moving objects and simple machines, but thinkers such as Aristotle and Archimedes retained fundamental errors in understanding force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In part, this was due to an incomplete understanding of the sometimes non-obvious force of friction and a consequently inadequate view of the nature of natural motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A fundamental error was the belief that a force is required to maintain motion, even at a constant velocity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Most of the previous misunderstandings about motion and force were eventually corrected by Galileo Galilei and Sir Isaac Newton.
[src:work-output/force-p01] With his mathematical insight, Newton formulated laws of motion that were not improved for over two hundred years.
[src:work-output/force-p01] By the early 20th century, Einstein developed a theory of relativity that correctly predicted the action of forces on objects with increasing momenta near the speed of light and also provided insight into the forces produced by gravitation and inertia.
[src:work-output/force-p01] With modern insights into quantum mechanics and technology that can accelerate particles close to the speed of light, particle physics has devised a Standard Model to describe forces between particles smaller than atoms.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The Standard Model predicts that exchanged particles called gauge bosons are the fundamental means by which forces are emitted and absorbed.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Only four main interactions are known: in order of decreasing strength, they are: strong, electromagnetic, weak, and gravitational.
[src:work-output/force-p01] High-energy particle physics observations made during the 1970s and 1980s confirmed that the weak and electromagnetic forces are expressions of a more fundamental electroweak interaction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Since antiquity the concept of force has been recognized as integral to the functioning of each of the simple machines.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The mechanical advantage given by a simple machine allowed for less force to be used in exchange for that force acting over a greater distance for the same amount of work.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Analysis of the characteristics of forces ultimately culminated in the work of Archimedes who was especially famous for formulating a treatment of buoyant forces inherent in fluids.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Aristotle provided a philosophical discussion of the concept of a force as an integral part of Aristotelian cosmology.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In Aristotle's view, the terrestrial sphere contained four elements that come to rest at different "natural places" therein.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Aristotle believed that motionless objects on Earth, those composed mostly of the elements earth and water, were in their natural place when on the ground, and that they stay that way if left alone.
[src:work-output/force-p01] He distinguished between the innate tendency of objects to find their "natural place" (e.g., for heavy bodies to fall), which led to "natural motion", and unnatural or forced motion, which required continued application of a force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This theory, based on the everyday experience of how objects move, such as the constant application of a force needed to keep a cart moving, had conceptual trouble accounting for the behavior of projectiles, such as the flight of arrows.
[src:work-output/force-p01] An archer causes the arrow to move at the start of the flight, and it then sails through the air even though no discernible efficient cause acts upon it.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Aristotle was aware of this problem and proposed that the air displaced through the projectile's path carries the projectile to its target.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This explanation requires a continuous medium such as air to sustain the motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Though Aristotelian physics was criticized as early as the 6th century, its shortcomings would not be corrected until the 17th century work of Galileo Galilei, who was influenced by the late medieval idea that objects in forced motion carried an innate force of impetus.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Galileo constructed an experiment in which stones and cannonballs were both rolled down an incline to disprove the Aristotelian theory of motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] He showed that the bodies were accelerated by gravity to an extent that was independent of their mass and argued that objects retain their velocity unless acted on by a force, for example friction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Galileo's idea that force is needed to change motion rather than to sustain it, further improved upon by Isaac Beeckman, René Descartes, and Pierre Gassendi, became a key principle of Newtonian physics.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In the early 17th century, before Newton's *Principia*, the term "force" (Latin: *vis*) was applied to many physical and non-physical phenomena, e.g., for an acceleration of a point.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The product of a point mass and the square of its velocity was named *vis viva* (live force) by Leibniz.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The modern concept of force corresponds to Newton's *vis motrix* (accelerating force).
[src:work-output/force-p01] Sir Isaac Newton described the motion of all objects using the concepts of inertia and force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In 1687, Newton published his magnum opus, *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In this work Newton set out three laws of motion that have dominated the way forces are described in physics to this day.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The precise ways in which Newton's laws are expressed have evolved in step with new mathematical approaches.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton's first law of motion states that the natural behavior of an object at rest is to continue being at rest, and the natural behavior of an object moving at constant speed in a straight line is to continue moving at that constant speed along that straight line.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The latter follows from the former because of the principle that the laws of physics are the same for all inertial observers, i.e., all observers who do not feel themselves to be in motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] An observer moving in tandem with an object will see it as being at rest.
[src:work-output/force-p01] So, its natural behavior will be to remain at rest with respect to that observer, which means that an observer who sees it moving at constant speed in a straight line will see it continuing to do so.
[src:work-output/force-p01] According to the first law, motion at constant speed in a straight line does not need a cause.
[src:work-output/force-p01] It is *change* in motion that requires a cause, and Newton's second law gives the quantitative relationship between force and change of motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton's second law states that the net force acting upon an object is equal to the rate at which its momentum changes with time.
[src:work-output/force-p01] If the mass of the object is constant, this law implies that the acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the net force acting on the object, is in the direction of the net force, and is inversely proportional to the mass of the object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A modern statement of Newton's second law is a vector equation: $\mathbf {F} ={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {p} }{\mathrm {d} t}},$ where $\mathbf {p}$ is the momentum of the system, and $\mathbf {F}$ is the net (vector sum) force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] If a body is in equilibrium, there is zero *net* force by definition (balanced forces may be present nevertheless).
[src:work-output/force-p01] In contrast, the second law states that if there is an *unbalanced* force acting on an object it will result in the object's momentum changing over time.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In common engineering applications the mass in a system remains constant allowing as simple algebraic form for the second law.
[src:work-output/force-p01] By the definition of momentum, $\mathbf {F} ={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {p} }{\mathrm {d} t}}={\frac {\mathrm {d} \left(m\mathbf {v} \right)}{\mathrm {d} t}},$ where *m* is the mass and $\mathbf {v}$ is the velocity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] If Newton's second law is applied to a system of constant mass, *m* may be moved outside the derivative operator.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Whenever one body exerts a force on another, the latter simultaneously exerts an equal and opposite force on the first.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton's third law is a result of applying symmetry to situations where forces can be attributed to the presence of different objects.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The third law means that all forces are *interactions* between different bodies. and thus that there is no such thing as a unidirectional force or a force that acts on only one body.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In a system composed of object 1 and object 2, the net force on the system due to their mutual interactions is zero: $\mathbf {F} _{1,2}+\mathbf {F} _{2,1}=0.$ More generally, in a closed system of particles, all internal forces are balanced.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The particles may accelerate with respect to each other but the center of mass of the system will not accelerate.
[src:work-output/force-p01] If an external force acts on the system, it will make the center of mass accelerate in proportion to the magnitude of the external force divided by the mass of the system.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Combining Newton's second and third laws, it is possible to show that the linear momentum of a system is conserved in any closed system.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In general, as long as all forces are due to the interaction of objects with mass, it is possible to define a system such that net momentum is never lost nor gained.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Some textbooks use Newton's second law as a *definition* of force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] However, for the equation $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ for a constant mass m to then have any predictive content, it must be combined with further information.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Moreover, inferring that a force is present because a body is accelerating is only valid in an inertial frame of reference.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The question of which aspects of Newton's laws to take as definitions and which to regard as holding physical content has been answered in various ways, which ultimately do not affect how the theory is used in practice.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Notable physicists, philosophers and mathematicians who have sought a more explicit definition of the concept of force include Ernst Mach and Walter Noll.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Forces act in a particular direction and have sizes dependent upon how strong the push or pull is.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Because of these characteristics, forces are classified as "vector quantities".
[src:work-output/force-p01] This means that forces follow a different set of mathematical rules than physical quantities that do not have direction (denoted scalar quantities).
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, when determining what happens when two forces act on the same object, it is necessary to know both the magnitude and the direction of both forces to calculate the result.
[src:work-output/force-p01] If both of these pieces of information are not known for each force, the situation is ambiguous.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Historically, forces were first quantitatively investigated in conditions of static equilibrium where several forces canceled each other out.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Such experiments demonstrate the crucial properties that forces are additive vector quantities: they have magnitude and direction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The magnitude of the resultant varies from the difference of the magnitudes of the two forces to their sum, depending on the angle between their lines of action.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Free-body diagrams can be used as a convenient way to keep track of forces acting on a system.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Ideally, these diagrams are drawn with the angles and relative magnitudes of the force vectors preserved so that graphical vector addition can be done to determine the net force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] As well as being added, forces can also be resolved into independent components at right angles to each other.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A horizontal force pointing northeast can therefore be split into two forces, one pointing north, and one pointing east.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Summing these component forces using vector addition yields the original force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Resolving force vectors into components of a set of basis vectors is often a more mathematically clean way to describe forces than using magnitudes and directions.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This is because, for orthogonal components, the components of the vector sum are uniquely determined by the scalar addition of the components of the individual vectors.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Orthogonal components are independent of each other because forces acting at ninety degrees to each other have no effect on the magnitude or direction of the other.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Choosing a set of orthogonal basis vectors is often done by considering what set of basis vectors will make the mathematics most convenient.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Choosing a basis vector that is in the same direction as one of the forces is desirable, since that force would then have only one non-zero component.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Orthogonal force vectors can be three-dimensional with the third component being at right angles to the other two.
[src:work-output/force-p01] When all the forces that act upon an object are balanced, then the object is said to be in a state of equilibrium.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Hence, equilibrium occurs when the resultant force acting on a point particle is zero (that is, the vector sum of all forces is zero).
[src:work-output/force-p01] When dealing with an extended body, it is also necessary that the net torque be zero.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A body is in *static equilibrium* with respect to a frame of reference if it at rest and not accelerating, whereas a body in *dynamic equilibrium* is moving at a constant speed in a straight line, i.e., moving but not accelerating.
[src:work-output/force-p01] What one observer sees as static equilibrium, another can see as dynamic equilibrium and vice versa.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Static equilibrium was understood well before the invention of classical mechanics.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Objects that are not accelerating have zero net force acting on them.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The simplest case of static equilibrium occurs when two forces are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, an object on a level surface is pulled (attracted) downward toward the center of the Earth by the force of gravity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] At the same time, a force is applied by the surface that resists the downward force with equal upward force (called a normal force).
[src:work-output/force-p01] The situation produces zero net force and hence no acceleration.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Pushing against an object that rests on a frictional surface can result in a situation where the object does not move because the applied force is opposed by static friction, generated between the object and the table surface.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For a situation with no movement, the static friction force *exactly* balances the applied force resulting in no acceleration.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The static friction increases or decreases in response to the applied force up to an upper limit determined by the characteristics of the contact between the surface and the object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A static equilibrium between two forces is the most usual way of measuring forces, using simple devices such as weighing scales and spring balances.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, an object suspended on a vertical spring scale experiences the force of gravity acting on the object balanced by a force applied by the "spring reaction force", which equals the object's weight.
[src:work-output/force-p01] These were all formulated and experimentally verified before Isaac Newton expounded his three laws of motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Dynamic equilibrium was first described by Galileo who noticed that certain assumptions of Aristotelian physics were contradicted by observations and logic.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Galileo realized that simple velocity addition demands that the concept of an "absolute rest frame" did not exist.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Galileo concluded that motion in a constant velocity was completely equivalent to rest.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This was contrary to Aristotle's notion of a "natural state" of rest that objects with mass naturally approached.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Simple experiments showed that Galileo's understanding of the equivalence of constant velocity and rest were correct.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, if a mariner dropped a cannonball from the crow's nest of a ship moving at a constant velocity, Aristotelian physics would have the cannonball fall straight down while the ship moved beneath it.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Thus, in an Aristotelian universe, the falling cannonball would land behind the foot of the mast of a moving ship.
[src:work-output/force-p01] When this experiment is actually conducted, the cannonball always falls at the foot of the mast, as if the cannonball knows to travel with the ship despite being separated from it.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Since there is no forward horizontal force being applied on the cannonball as it falls, the only conclusion left is that the cannonball continues to move with the same velocity as the boat as it falls.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Thus, no force is required to keep the cannonball moving at the constant forward velocity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Moreover, any object traveling at a constant velocity must be subject to zero net force (resultant force).
[src:work-output/force-p01] This is the definition of dynamic equilibrium: when all the forces on an object balance but it still moves at a constant velocity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A simple case of dynamic equilibrium occurs in constant velocity motion across a surface with kinetic friction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In such a situation, a force is applied in the direction of motion while the kinetic friction force exactly opposes the applied force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This results in zero net force, but since the object started with a non-zero velocity, it continues to move with a non-zero velocity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Aristotle misinterpreted this motion as being caused by the applied force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] When kinetic friction is taken into consideration it is clear that there is no net force causing constant velocity motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Some forces are consequences of the fundamental ones.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In such situations, idealized models can be used to gain physical insight.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, each solid object is considered a rigid body.
[src:work-output/force-p01] What we now call gravity was not identified as a universal force until the work of Isaac Newton.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Before Newton, the tendency for objects to fall towards the Earth was not understood to be related to the motions of celestial objects.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Galileo was instrumental in describing the characteristics of falling objects by determining that the acceleration of every object in free-fall was constant and independent of the mass of the object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Today, this acceleration due to gravity towards the surface of the Earth is usually designated as $\mathbf {g}$ and has a magnitude of about 9.81 meters per second squared (this measurement is taken from sea level and may vary depending on location), and points toward the center of the Earth.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This observation means that the force of gravity on an object at the Earth's surface is directly proportional to the object's mass.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For an object in free-fall, this force is unopposed and the net force on the object is its weight.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For objects not in free-fall, the force of gravity is opposed by the reaction forces applied by their supports.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, a person standing on the ground experiences zero net force, since a normal force (a reaction force) is exerted by the ground upward on the person that counterbalances his weight that is directed downward.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton's contribution to gravitational theory was to unify the motions of heavenly bodies, which Aristotle had assumed were in a natural state of constant motion, with falling motion observed on the Earth.
[src:work-output/force-p01] He proposed a law of gravity that could account for the celestial motions that had been described earlier using Kepler's laws of planetary motion.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton came to realize that the effects of gravity might be observed in different ways at larger distances.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In particular, Newton determined that the acceleration of the Moon around the Earth could be ascribed to the same force of gravity if the acceleration due to gravity decreased as an inverse square law.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Further, Newton realized that the acceleration of a body due to gravity is proportional to the mass of the other attracting body.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In this equation, a dimensional constant G is used to describe the relative strength of gravity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This constant has come to be known as the Newtonian constant of gravitation, though its value was unknown in Newton's lifetime.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Not until 1798 was Henry Cavendish able to make the first measurement of G using a torsion balance; this was widely reported in the press as a measurement of the mass of the Earth since knowing G could allow one to solve for the Earth's mass given the above equation.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton realized that since all celestial bodies followed the same laws of motion, his law of gravity had to be universal.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This formula was powerful enough to stand as the basis for all subsequent descriptions of motion within the Solar System until the 20th century.
[src:work-output/force-p01] During that time, sophisticated methods of perturbation analysis were invented to calculate the deviations of orbits due to the influence of multiple bodies on a planet, moon, comet, or asteroid.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The formalism was exact enough to allow mathematicians to predict the existence of the planet Neptune before it was observed.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The electrostatic force was first described in 1784 by Coulomb as a force that existed intrinsically between two charges.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The properties of the electrostatic force were that it varied as an inverse square law directed in the radial direction, was both attractive and repulsive (there was intrinsic polarity), was independent of the mass of the charged objects, and followed the superposition principle.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Coulomb's law unifies all these observations into one succinct statement.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Subsequent mathematicians and physicists found the construct of the *electric field* to be useful for determining the electrostatic force on an electric charge at any point in space.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The electric field was based on using a hypothetical "test charge" anywhere in space and then using Coulomb's law to determine the electrostatic force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Thus the electric field anywhere in space is defined as $\mathbf {E} ={\mathbf {F} \over {q}},$ where q is the magnitude of the hypothetical test charge.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Similarly, the idea of the *magnetic field* was introduced to express how magnets can influence one another at a distance.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The magnetic contribution to the Lorentz force is the cross product of the velocity vector with the magnetic field.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The origin of electric and magnetic fields would not be fully explained until 1864 when James Clerk Maxwell unified a number of earlier theories into a set of 20 scalar equations, which were later reformulated into 4 vector equations by Oliver Heaviside and Josiah Willard Gibbs.
[src:work-output/force-p01] These "Maxwell's equations" fully described the sources of the fields as being stationary and moving charges, and the interactions of the fields themselves.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This led Maxwell to discover that electric and magnetic fields could be "self-generating" through a wave that traveled at a speed that he calculated to be the speed of light.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This insight united the nascent fields of electromagnetic theory with optics and led directly to a complete description of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:work-output/force-p01] When objects are in contact, the force directly between them is called the normal force, the component of the total force in the system exerted normal to the interface between the objects.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The normal force is closely related to Newton's third law.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The normal force, for example, is responsible for the structural integrity of tables and floors as well as being the force that responds whenever an external force pushes on a solid object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] An example of the normal force in action is the impact force on an object crashing into an immobile surface.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Friction is a force that opposes relative motion of two bodies.
[src:work-output/force-p01] At the macroscopic scale, the frictional force is directly related to the normal force at the point of contact.
[src:work-output/force-p01] There are two broad classifications of frictional forces: static friction and kinetic friction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The static friction force ( $\mathbf {F} _{\mathrm {sf} }$ ) will exactly oppose forces applied to an object parallel to a surface up to the limit specified by the coefficient of static friction ( $\mu _{\mathrm {sf} }$ ) multiplied by the normal force ( $\mathbf {F} _{\text{N}}$ ).
[src:work-output/force-p01] The kinetic friction force ( $F_{\mathrm {kf} }$ ) is typically independent of both the forces applied and the movement of the object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] where $\mu _{\mathrm {kf} }$ is the coefficient of kinetic friction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The coefficient of kinetic friction is normally less than the coefficient of static friction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Tension forces can be modeled using ideal strings that are massless, frictionless, unbreakable, and do not stretch.
[src:work-output/force-p01] They can be combined with ideal pulleys, which allow ideal strings to switch physical direction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Ideal strings transmit tension forces instantaneously in action–reaction pairs so that if two objects are connected by an ideal string, any force directed along the string by the first object is accompanied by a force directed along the string in the opposite direction by the second object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] By connecting the same string multiple times to the same object through the use of a configuration that uses movable pulleys, the tension force on a load can be multiplied.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For every string that acts on a load, another factor of the tension force in the string acts on the load.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Such machines allow a mechanical advantage for a corresponding increase in the length of displaced string needed to move the load.
[src:work-output/force-p01] These tandem effects result ultimately in the conservation of mechanical energy since the work done on the load is the same no matter how complicated the machine.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A simple elastic force acts to return a spring to its natural length.
[src:work-output/force-p01] An ideal spring is taken to be massless, frictionless, unbreakable, and infinitely stretchable.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Such springs exert forces that push when contracted, or pull when extended, in proportion to the displacement of the spring from its equilibrium position.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This linear relationship was described by Robert Hooke in 1676, for whom Hooke's law is named.
[src:work-output/force-p01] If $\Delta x$ is the displacement, the force exerted by an ideal spring equals: $\mathbf {F} =-k\Delta \mathbf {x} ,$ where k is the spring constant (or force constant), which is particular to the spring.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The minus sign accounts for the tendency of the force to act in opposition to the applied load.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This means that the net force felt by the object is always directed toward the center of the curving path.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Such forces act perpendicular to the velocity vector associated with the motion of an object, and therefore do not change the speed of the object (magnitude of the velocity), but only the direction of the velocity vector.
[src:work-output/force-p01] More generally, the net force that accelerates an object can be resolved into a component that is perpendicular to the path, and one that is tangential to the path.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This yields both the tangential force, which accelerates the object by either slowing it down or speeding it up, and the radial (centripetal) force, which changes its direction.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton's laws and Newtonian mechanics in general were first developed to describe how forces affect idealized point particles rather than three-dimensional objects.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In real life, matter has extended structure and forces that act on one part of an object might affect other parts of an object.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For situations where lattice holding together the atoms in an object is able to flow, contract, expand, or otherwise change shape, the theories of continuum mechanics describe the way forces affect the material.
[src:work-output/force-p01] where V is the volume of the object in the fluid and P is the scalar function that describes the pressure at all locations in space.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Pressure gradients and differentials result in the buoyant force for fluids suspended in gravitational fields, winds in atmospheric science, and the lift associated with aerodynamics and flight.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A specific instance of such a force that is associated with dynamic pressure is fluid resistance: a body force that resists the motion of an object through a fluid due to viscosity.
[src:work-output/force-p01] More formally, forces in continuum mechanics are fully described by a stress tensor with terms that are roughly defined as $\sigma ={\frac {F}{A}},$ where A is the relevant cross-sectional area for the volume for which the stress tensor is being calculated.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This formalism includes pressure terms associated with forces that act normal to the cross-sectional area (the matrix diagonals of the tensor) as well as shear terms associated with forces that act parallel to the cross-sectional area (the off-diagonal elements).
[src:work-output/force-p01] The stress tensor accounts for forces that cause all strains (deformations) including also tensile stresses and compressions.
[src:work-output/force-p01] There are forces that are frame dependent, meaning that they appear due to the adoption of non-Newtonian (that is, non-inertial) reference frames.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Such forces include the centrifugal force and the Coriolis force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] These forces are considered fictitious because they do not exist in frames of reference that are not accelerating.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Because these forces are not genuine they are also referred to as "pseudo forces".
[src:work-output/force-p01] In general relativity, gravity becomes a fictitious force that arises in situations where spacetime deviates from a flat geometry.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Forces that cause extended objects to rotate are associated with torques.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Mathematically, the torque of a force $\mathbf {F}$ is defined relative to an arbitrary reference point as the cross product: ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {F} ,$ where $\mathbf {r}$ is the position vector of the force application point relative to the reference point.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Torque is the rotation equivalent of force in the same way that angle is the rotational equivalent for position, angular velocity for velocity, and angular momentum for momentum.
[src:work-output/force-p01] As a consequence of Newton's first law of motion, there exists rotational inertia that ensures that all bodies maintain their angular momentum unless acted upon by an unbalanced torque.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This provides a definition for the moment of inertia, which is the rotational equivalent for mass.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In more advanced treatments of mechanics, where the rotation over a time interval is described, the moment of inertia must be substituted by the tensor that, when properly analyzed, fully determines the characteristics of rotations including precession and nutation.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Equivalently, the differential form of Newton's second law provides an alternative definition of torque: ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {L} }{\mathrm {dt} }},$ where $\mathbf {L}$ is the angular momentum of the particle.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Newton's third law of motion requires that all objects exerting torques themselves experience equal and opposite torques, and therefore also directly implies the conservation of angular momentum for closed systems that experience rotations and revolutions through the action of internal torques.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The term is used in biomechanical analysis, athletic assessment and robotic control.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The second ("tug"), third ("snatch"), fourth ("shake"), and higher derivatives are rarely used.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Forces can be used to define a number of physical concepts by integrating with respect to kinematic variables.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, integrating with respect to time gives the definition of impulse: $\mathbf {J} =\int _{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}{\mathbf {F} \,\mathrm {d} t},$ which by Newton's second law must be equivalent to the change in momentum (yielding the Impulse momentum theorem).
[src:work-output/force-p01] Similarly, integrating with respect to position gives a definition for the work done by a force: $W=\int _{\mathbf {x} _{1}}^{\mathbf {x} _{2}}{\mathbf {F} \cdot {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {x} }},$ which is equivalent to changes in kinetic energy (yielding the work energy theorem).
[src:work-output/force-p01] Instead of a force, often the mathematically related concept of a potential energy field is used.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For instance, the gravitational force acting upon an object can be seen as the action of the gravitational field that is present at the object's location.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Forces can be classified as conservative or nonconservative.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Conservative forces are equivalent to the gradient of a potential while nonconservative forces are not.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A conservative force that acts on a closed system has an associated mechanical work that allows energy to convert only between kinetic or potential forms.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This means that for a closed system, the net mechanical energy is conserved whenever a conservative force acts on the system.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Conservative forces include gravity, the electromagnetic force, and the spring force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Each of these forces has models that are dependent on a position often given as a radial vector $\mathbf {r}$ emanating from spherically symmetric potentials.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For electrostatic forces: $\mathbf {F} _{\text{e}}={\frac {q_{1}q_{2}}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}r^{2}}}{\hat {\mathbf {r} }},$ where $\varepsilon _{0}$ is electric permittivity of free space, and $q_{n}$ is the electric charge of object *n*.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For spring forces: $\mathbf {F} _{\text{s}}=-kr{\hat {\mathbf {r} }},$ where k is the spring constant.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For certain physical scenarios, it is impossible to model forces as being due to a simple gradient of potentials.
[src:work-output/force-p01] This is often due a macroscopic statistical average of microstates.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For example, static friction is caused by the gradients of numerous electrostatic potentials between the atoms, but manifests as a force model that is independent of any macroscale position vector.
[src:work-output/force-p01] Nonconservative forces other than friction include other contact forces, tension, compression, and drag.
[src:work-output/force-p01] For any sufficiently detailed description, all these forces are the results of conservative ones since each of these macroscopic forces are the net results of the gradients of microscopic potentials.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The connection between macroscopic nonconservative forces and microscopic conservative forces is described by detailed treatment with statistical mechanics.
[src:work-output/force-p01] In macroscopic closed systems, nonconservative forces act to change the internal energies of the system, and are often associated with the transfer of heat.
[src:work-output/force-p01] According to the Second law of thermodynamics, nonconservative forces necessarily result in energy transformations within closed systems from ordered to more random conditions as entropy increases.
[src:work-output/force-p01] A newton is thus equal to 100,000 dynes.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The gravitational foot-pound-second English unit of force is the pound-force (lbf), defined as the force exerted by gravity on a pound-mass in the standard gravitational field of 9.80665 m·s−2.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The pound-force provides an alternative unit of mass: one slug is the mass that will accelerate by one foot per second squared when acted on by one pound-force.
[src:work-output/force-p01] An alternative unit of force in a different foot–pound–second system, the absolute fps system, is the poundal, defined as the force required to accelerate a one-pound mass at a rate of one foot per second squared.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The pound-force has a metric counterpart, less commonly used than the newton: the kilogram-force (kgf) (sometimes kilopond), is the force exerted by standard gravity on one kilogram of mass.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The kilogram-force leads to an alternate, but rarely used unit of mass: the metric slug (sometimes mug or hyl) is that mass that accelerates at 1 m·s−2 when subjected to a force of 1 kgf.
[src:work-output/force-p01] The kilogram-force is not a part of the modern SI system, and is generally deprecated, sometimes used for expressing aircraft weight, jet thrust, bicycle spoke tension, torque wrench settings and engine output torque.
[src:work-output/force-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, new physical ideas emerged to explain experimental results in astronomical and submicroscopic realms.
[src:work-output/force-p02] As discussed below, relativity alters the definition of momentum and quantum mechanics reuses the concept of "force" in microscopic contexts where Newton's laws do not apply directly.
[src:work-output/force-p02] In the special theory of relativity, mass and energy are equivalent (as can be seen by calculating the work required to accelerate an object).
[src:work-output/force-p02] When an object's velocity increases, so does its energy and hence its mass equivalent (inertia).
[src:work-output/force-p02] It thus requires more force to accelerate it the same amount than it did at a lower velocity.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Newton's second law, $\mathbf {F} ={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {p} }{\mathrm {d} t}},$ remains valid because it is a mathematical definition.
[src:work-output/force-p02] But for momentum to be conserved at relativistic relative velocity, v , momentum must be redefined as: $\mathbf {p} ={\frac {m_{0}\mathbf {v} }{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}},$ where $m_{0}$ is the rest mass and c the speed of light.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The expression relating force and acceleration for a particle with constant non-zero rest mass m moving in the x direction at velocity v is: $\mathbf {F} =\left(\gamma ^{3}ma_{x},\gamma ma_{y},\gamma ma_{z}\right),$ where $\gamma ={\frac {1}{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}}.$ is called the Lorentz factor.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The Lorentz factor increases steeply as the relative velocity approaches the speed of light.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Consequently, the greater and greater force must be applied to produce the same acceleration at extreme velocity.
[src:work-output/force-p02] If v is very small compared to c , then $\gamma$ is very close to 1 and $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ is a close approximation.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Even for use in relativity, one can restore the form of $F^{\mu }=mA^{\mu }$ through the use of four-vectors.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This relation is correct in relativity when $F^{\mu }$ is the four-force, m is the invariant mass, and $A^{\mu }$ is the four-acceleration.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The *general* theory of relativity incorporates a more radical departure from the Newtonian way of thinking about force, specifically gravitational force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This reimagining of the nature of gravity is described more fully below.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Quantum mechanics is a theory of physics originally developed in order to understand microscopic phenomena: behavior at the scale of molecules, atoms or subatomic particles.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Generally and loosely speaking, the smaller a system is, the more an adequate mathematical model will require understanding quantum effects.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The conceptual underpinning of quantum physics is different from that of classical physics.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Instead of thinking about quantities like position, momentum, and energy as properties that an object *has*, one considers what result might *appear* when a measurement of a chosen type is performed.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Quantum mechanics allows the physicist to calculate the probability that a chosen measurement will elicit a particular result.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The expectation value for a measurement is the average of the possible results it might yield, weighted by their probabilities of occurrence.
[src:work-output/force-p02] In quantum mechanics, interactions are typically described in terms of energy rather than force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The Ehrenfest theorem provides a connection between quantum expectation values and the classical concept of force, a connection that is necessarily inexact, as quantum physics is fundamentally different from classical.
[src:work-output/force-p02] In quantum physics, the Born rule is used to calculate the expectation values of a position measurement or a momentum measurement.
[src:work-output/force-p02] These expectation values will generally change over time; that is, depending on the time at which (for example) a position measurement is performed, the probabilities for its different possible outcomes will vary.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The Ehrenfest theorem says, roughly speaking, that the equations describing how these expectation values change over time have a form reminiscent of Newton's second law, with a force defined as the negative derivative of the potential energy.
[src:work-output/force-p02] However, the more pronounced quantum effects are in a given situation, the more difficult it is to derive meaningful conclusions from this resemblance.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Quantum mechanics also introduces two new constraints that interact with forces at the submicroscopic scale and which are especially important for atoms.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Despite the strong attraction of the nucleus, the uncertainty principle limits the minimum extent of an electron probability distribution and the Pauli exclusion principle prevents electrons from sharing the same probability distribution.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This gives rise to an emergent pressure known as degeneracy pressure.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The dynamic equilibrium between the degeneracy pressure and the attractive electromagnetic force give atoms, molecules, liquids, and solids stability.
[src:work-output/force-p02] In modern particle physics, forces and the acceleration of particles are explained as a mathematical by-product of exchange of momentum-carrying gauge bosons.
[src:work-output/force-p02] With the development of quantum field theory and general relativity, it was realized that force is a redundant concept arising from conservation of momentum (4-momentum in relativity and momentum of virtual particles in quantum electrodynamics).
[src:work-output/force-p02] The conservation of momentum can be directly derived from the homogeneity or symmetry of space and so is usually considered more fundamental than the concept of a force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Thus the currently known fundamental forces are considered more accurately to be "fundamental interactions".
[src:work-output/force-p02] While sophisticated mathematical descriptions are needed to predict, in full detail, the result of such interactions, there is a conceptually simple way to describe them through the use of Feynman diagrams.
[src:work-output/force-p02] In a Feynman diagram, each matter particle is represented as a straight line (see world line) traveling through time, which normally increases up or to the right in the diagram.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Matter and anti-matter particles are identical except for their direction of propagation through the Feynman diagram.
[src:work-output/force-p02] World lines of particles intersect at interaction vertices, and the Feynman diagram represents any force arising from an interaction as occurring at the vertex with an associated instantaneous change in the direction of the particle world lines.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Gauge bosons are emitted away from the vertex as wavy lines and, in the case of virtual particle exchange, are absorbed at an adjacent vertex.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The utility of Feynman diagrams is that other types of physical phenomena that are part of the general picture of fundamental interactions but are conceptually separate from forces can also be described using the same rules.
[src:work-output/force-p02] For example, a Feynman diagram can describe in succinct detail how a neutron decays into an electron, proton, and antineutrino, an interaction mediated by the same gauge boson that is responsible for the weak nuclear force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] All of the known forces of the universe are classified into four fundamental interactions.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The strong and the weak forces act only at very short distances, and are responsible for the interactions between subatomic particles, including nucleons and compound nuclei.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The electromagnetic force acts between electric charges, and the gravitational force acts between masses.
[src:work-output/force-p02] All other forces in nature derive from these four fundamental interactions operating within quantum mechanics, including the constraints introduced by the Schrödinger equation and the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:work-output/force-p02] For example, friction is a manifestation of the electromagnetic force acting between atoms of two surfaces.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The forces in springs, modeled by Hooke's law, are also the result of electromagnetic forces.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Centrifugal forces are acceleration forces that arise simply from the acceleration of rotating frames of reference.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The fundamental theories for forces developed from the unification of different ideas.
[src:work-output/force-p02] For example, Newton's universal theory of gravitation showed that the force responsible for objects falling near the surface of the Earth is also the force responsible for the falling of celestial bodies about the Earth (the Moon) and around the Sun (the planets).
[src:work-output/force-p02] Michael Faraday and James Clerk Maxwell demonstrated that electric and magnetic forces were unified through a theory of electromagnetism.
[src:work-output/force-p02] In the 20th century, the development of quantum mechanics led to a modern understanding that the first three fundamental forces (all except gravity) are manifestations of matter (fermions) interacting by exchanging virtual particles called gauge bosons.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This Standard Model of particle physics assumes a similarity between the forces and led scientists to predict the unification of the weak and electromagnetic forces in electroweak theory, which was subsequently confirmed by observation.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Newton's law of gravitation is an example of *action at a distance*: one body, like the Sun, exerts an influence upon any other body, like the Earth, no matter how far apart they are.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Moreover, this action at a distance is *instantaneous.* According to Newton's theory, the one body shifting position changes the gravitational pulls felt by all other bodies, all at the same instant of time.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Albert Einstein recognized that this was inconsistent with special relativity and its prediction that influences cannot travel faster than the speed of light.
[src:work-output/force-p02] So, he sought a new theory of gravitation that would be relativistically consistent.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Mercury's orbit did not match that predicted by Newton's law of gravitation.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Some astrophysicists predicted the existence of an undiscovered planet (Vulcan) that could explain the discrepancies.
[src:work-output/force-p02] When Einstein formulated his theory of general relativity (GR) he focused on Mercury's problematic orbit and found that his theory added a correction, which could account for the discrepancy.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This was the first time that Newton's theory of gravity had been shown to be inexact.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Since then, general relativity has been acknowledged as the theory that best explains gravity.
[src:work-output/force-p02] In GR, gravitation is not viewed as a force, but rather, objects moving freely in gravitational fields travel under their own inertia in straight lines through curved spacetime – defined as the shortest spacetime path between two spacetime events.
[src:work-output/force-p02] From the perspective of the object, all motion occurs as if there were no gravitation whatsoever.
[src:work-output/force-p02] It is only when observing the motion in a global sense that the curvature of spacetime can be observed and the force is inferred from the object's curved path.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Thus, the straight line path in spacetime is seen as a curved line in space, and it is called the *ballistic trajectory* of the object.
[src:work-output/force-p02] For example, a basketball thrown from the ground moves in a parabola, as it is in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Its spacetime trajectory is almost a straight line, slightly curved (with the radius of curvature of the order of few light-years).
[src:work-output/force-p02] The time derivative of the changing momentum of the object is what we label as "gravitational force".
[src:work-output/force-p02] Maxwell's equations and the set of techniques built around them adequately describe a wide range of physics involving force in electricity and magnetism.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This classical theory already includes relativity effects.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Understanding quantized electromagnetic interactions between elementary particles requires quantum electrodynamics (QED).
[src:work-output/force-p02] In QED, photons are fundamental exchange particles, describing all interactions relating to electromagnetism including the electromagnetic force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] There are two "nuclear forces", which today are usually described as interactions that take place in quantum theories of particle physics.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The strong nuclear force is the force responsible for the structural integrity of atomic nuclei, and gains its name from its ability to overpower the electromagnetic repulsion between protons.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The strong force is today understood to represent the interactions between quarks and gluons as detailed by the theory of quantum chromodynamics (QCD).
[src:work-output/force-p02] The strong force is the fundamental force mediated by gluons, acting upon quarks, antiquarks, and the gluons themselves.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The strong force only acts *directly* upon elementary particles.
[src:work-output/force-p02] A residual is observed between hadrons (notably, the nucleons in atomic nuclei), known as the nuclear force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Here the strong force acts indirectly, transmitted as gluons that form part of the virtual pi and rho mesons, the classical transmitters of the nuclear force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The failure of many searches for free quarks has shown that the elementary particles affected are not directly observable.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This phenomenon is called color confinement.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Unique among the fundamental interactions, the weak nuclear force creates no bound states.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The weak force is due to the exchange of the heavy W and Z bosons.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Since the weak force is mediated by two types of bosons, it can be divided into two types of interaction or "vertices" — charged current, involving the electrically charged W+ and W− bosons, and neutral current, involving electrically neutral Z0 bosons.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The most familiar effect of weak interaction is beta decay (of neutrons in atomic nuclei) and the associated radioactivity.
[src:work-output/force-p02] This is a type of charged-current interaction.
[src:work-output/force-p02] The word "weak" derives from the fact that the field strength is some 1013 times less than that of the strong force.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Still, it is stronger than gravity over short distances.
[src:work-output/force-p02] A consistent electroweak theory has also been developed, which shows that electromagnetic forces and the weak force are indistinguishable at a temperatures in excess of approximately 1015 K.
[src:work-output/force-p02] Such temperatures occurred in the plasma collisions in the early moments of the Big Bang.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A **heat engine** is a system that transfers thermal energy to do mechanical or electrical work.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] While originally conceived in the context of mechanical energy, the concept of the heat engine has been applied to various other kinds of energy, particularly electrical, since at least the late 19th century.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The heat engine does this by bringing a working substance from a higher state temperature to a lower state temperature.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A heat source supplies thermal energy that brings the working substance to the higher temperature state.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The working substance does work in the working body of the engine while transferring heat to the colder sink until it reaches a lower temperature state.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] During this process some of the thermal energy is converted into work by exploiting the properties of the working substance.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The working substance can be any system with a non-zero heat capacity, but it usually is a gas or liquid.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] During this process, some heat is normally lost to the surroundings and is not converted to work.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Also, in a mechanical engine, some energy is unusable because of friction and drag.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In general, an engine is any machine that converts energy to mechanical work.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Heat engines distinguish themselves from other types of engines by the fact that their efficiency is fundamentally limited by Carnot's theorem of thermodynamics.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Since the heat source that supplies thermal energy to the engine can thus be powered by virtually any kind of energy, heat engines cover a wide range of applications.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Heat engines are often confused with the cycles they attempt to implement.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Typically, the term "engine" is used for a physical device and "cycle" for the models; thus, for example, a diesel engine is a machine which implements the Diesel cycle.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In thermodynamics, heat engines are often modeled using a standard engineering model such as the Otto cycle.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The theoretical model can be refined and augmented with actual data from an operating engine, using tools such as an indicator diagram.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Since very few actual implementations of heat engines exactly match their underlying thermodynamic cycles, one could say that a thermodynamic cycle is an ideal case of a mechanical engine.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In any case, fully understanding an engine and its efficiency requires a good understanding of the (possibly simplified or idealised) theoretical model, the practical nuances of an actual mechanical engine and the discrepancies between the two.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In general terms, the larger the difference in temperature between the hot source and the cold sink, the larger is the potential thermal efficiency of the cycle.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The maximum theoretical efficiency of a heat engine (which no engine ever attains) is equal to the temperature difference between the hot and cold ends divided by the temperature at the hot end, each expressed in absolute temperature.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The efficiency of these processes is roughly proportional to the temperature drop across them.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Significant energy may be consumed by auxiliary equipment, such as pumps, which effectively reduces efficiency.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Although some cycles have a typical combustion location (internal or external), they can often be implemented with the other.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] For example, John Ericsson developed an external heated engine running on a cycle very much like the earlier Diesel cycle.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In addition, externally heated engines can often be implemented in open or closed cycles.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Everyday examples of heat engines include the thermal power station, internal combustion engine, firearms, refrigerators and heat pumps.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Power stations are examples of heat engines run in a forward direction in which heat flows from a hot reservoir and flows into a cool reservoir to produce work as the desired product.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Refrigerators remove heat from within a thermally sealed chamber at low temperature and vent waste heat at a higher temperature to the environment and heat pumps take heat from the low temperature environment and 'vent' it into a thermally sealed chamber (a house) at higher temperature.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In general heat engines exploit the thermal properties associated with the expansion and compression of gases according to the gas laws or the properties associated with phase changes between gas and liquid states.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Earth's atmosphere and hydrosphere—Earth's heat engine—are coupled processes that constantly even out solar heating imbalances through evaporation of surface water, convection, rainfall, winds and ocean circulation, when distributing heat around the globe.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A Hadley cell is an example of a heat engine.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] It involves the rising of warm and moist air in the earth's equatorial region and the descent of colder air in the subtropics creating a thermally driven direct circulation, with consequent net production of kinetic energy.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In phase change cycles and engines, the working fluids are gases and liquids.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The engine converts the working fluid from a gas to a liquid, from liquid to gas, or both, generating work from the fluid expansion or compression.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A domestic refrigerator is an example of a heat pump: a heat engine in reverse.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Work is used to create a heat differential.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Many cycles can run in reverse to move heat from the cold side to the hot side, making the cold side cooler and the hot side hotter.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Internal combustion engine versions of these cycles are, by their nature, not reversible.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The Barton evaporation engine is a heat engine based on a cycle producing power and cooled moist air from the evaporation of water into hot dry air.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Mesoscopic heat engines are nanoscale devices that may serve the goal of processing heat fluxes and perform useful work at small scales.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Potential applications include e.g. electric cooling devices.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In such mesoscopic heat engines, work per cycle of operation fluctuates due to thermal noise.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] There is exact equality that relates average of exponents of work performed by any heat engine and the heat transfer from the hotter heat bath.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] This relation transforms the Carnot's inequality into exact equality.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The efficiency of a heat engine relates how much useful work is output for a given amount of heat energy input.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In other words, a heat engine absorbs heat energy from the high temperature heat source, converting part of it to useful work and giving off the rest as waste heat to the cold temperature heat sink.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In general, the efficiency of a given heat transfer process is defined by the ratio of "what is taken out" to "what is put in".
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The efficiency is less than 100% because of the waste heat $Q_{c}<0$ unavoidably lost to the cold sink (and corresponding compression work put in) during the required recompression at the cold temperature before the power stroke of the engine can occur again.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The *theoretical* maximum efficiency of any heat engine depends only on the temperatures it operates between.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] This efficiency is usually derived using an ideal imaginary heat engine such as the Carnot heat engine, although other engines using different cycles can also attain maximum efficiency.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Note that $\Delta S_{h}$ is positive because isothermal expansion in the power stroke increases the multiplicity of the working fluid while $\Delta S_{c}$ is negative since recompression decreases the multiplicity.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] where $T_{h}$ is the absolute temperature of the hot source and $T_{c}$ that of the cold sink, usually measured in kelvins.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The reasoning behind this being the **maximal** efficiency goes as follows.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] It is first assumed that if a more efficient heat engine than a Carnot engine is possible, then it could be driven in reverse as a heat pump.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Mathematical analysis can be used to show that this assumed combination would result in a net decrease in entropy.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Since, by the second law of thermodynamics, this is statistically improbable to the point of exclusion, the Carnot efficiency is a theoretical upper bound on the reliable efficiency of *any* thermodynamic cycle.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Empirically, no heat engine has ever been shown to run at a greater efficiency than a Carnot cycle heat engine.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Figure 2 and Figure 3 show variations on Carnot cycle efficiency with temperature.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Figure 2 indicates how efficiency changes with an increase in the heat addition temperature for a constant compressor inlet temperature.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Figure 3 indicates how the efficiency changes with an increase in the heat rejection temperature for a constant turbine inlet temperature.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] By its nature, any maximally efficient Carnot cycle must operate at an infinitesimal temperature gradient; this is because any transfer of heat between two bodies of differing temperatures is irreversible, therefore the Carnot efficiency expression applies only to the infinitesimal limit.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The major problem is that the objective of most heat-engines is to output power, and infinitesimal power is seldom desired.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A different measure of ideal heat-engine efficiency is given by considerations of endoreversible thermodynamics, where the system is broken into reversible subsystems, but with non reversible interactions between them.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A classical example is the Curzon–Ahlborn engine, very similar to a Carnot engine, but where the thermal reservoirs at temperature $T_{h}$ and $T_{c}$ are allowed to be different from the temperatures of the substance going through the reversible Carnot cycle: $T'_{h}$ and $T'_{c}$ .
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The heat transfers between the reservoirs and the substance are considered as conductive (and irreversible) in the form $dQ_{h,c}/dt=\alpha (T_{h,c}-T'_{h,c})$ .
[src:work-output/heat-engine] In this case, a tradeoff has to be made between power output and efficiency.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] If the engine is operated very slowly, the heat flux is low, $T\approx T'$ and the classical Carnot result is found $\eta =1-{\frac {T_{c}}{T_{h}}},$ but at the price of a vanishing power output.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] As shown, the Curzon–Ahlborn efficiency much more closely models that observed.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Heat engines have been known since antiquity but were only made into useful devices at the time of the industrial revolution in the 18th century.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Engineers have studied the various heat-engine cycles to improve the amount of usable work they could extract from a given power source.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Exploit the physical properties of the working fluid.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The most common such exploitation is the use of water above the critical point (supercritical water).
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A newer and very promising material for such applications is supercritical CO2.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] SO2 and xenon have also been considered for such applications.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Downsides include issues of corrosion and erosion, the different chemical behavior above and below the critical point, the needed high pressures and – in the case of sulfur dioxide and to a lesser extent carbon dioxide – toxicity.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Among the mentioned compounds xenon is least suitable for use in a nuclear reactor due to the high neutron absorption cross section of almost all isotopes of xenon, whereas carbon dioxide and water can also double as a neutron moderator for a thermal spectrum reactor.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Exploit the chemical properties of the working fluid.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] A fairly new and novel exploit is to use exotic working fluids with advantageous chemical properties.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] One such is nitrogen dioxide (NO2), a toxic component of smog, which has a natural dimer as di-nitrogen tetraoxide (N2O4).
[src:work-output/heat-engine] At low temperature, the N2O4 is compressed and then heated.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] The increasing temperature causes each N2O4 to break apart into two NO2 molecules.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] This lowers the molecular weight of the working fluid, which drastically increases the efficiency of the cycle.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Once the NO2 has expanded through the turbine, it is cooled by the heat sink, which makes it recombine into N2O4.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] This is then fed back by the compressor for another cycle.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] Such species as aluminium bromide (Al2Br6), NOCl, and Ga2I6 have all been investigated for such uses.
[src:work-output/heat-engine] To date, their drawbacks have not warranted their use, despite the efficiency gains that can be realized.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In science, **work** is the energy transferred to or from an object via the application of force along a displacement.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In its simplest form, for a constant force aligned with the direction of motion, the work equals the product of the force strength and the distance traveled.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] A force is said to do *positive work* if it has a component in the direction of the displacement of the point of application.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] A force does *negative work* if it has a component opposite to the direction of the displacement at the point of application of the force.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] For example, when a ball is held above the ground and then dropped, the work done by the gravitational force on the ball as it falls is positive, and is equal to the weight of the ball (a force) multiplied by the distance to the ground (a displacement).
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] If the ball is thrown upwards, the work done by the gravitational force is negative, and is equal to the weight multiplied by the displacement in the upwards direction.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Both force and displacement are vectors.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work done is given by the dot product of the two vectors, where the result is a scalar.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] where $d\mathbf {s}$ is the infinitesimal change in displacement vector, $dt$ is the infinitesimal increment of time, and $\mathbf {v}$ represents the velocity vector.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The first equation represents force as a function of the position and the second and third equations represent force as a function of time.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Work is a scalar quantity, so it has only magnitude and no direction.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Work transfers energy from one place to another, or one form to another.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The SI unit of work is the joule (J), the same unit as for energy.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The ancient Greek understanding of physics was limited to the statics of simple machines (the balance of forces), and did not include dynamics or the concept of work.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The complete dynamic theory of simple machines was worked out by Italian scientist Galileo Galilei in 1600 in *Le Meccaniche* (*On Mechanics*), in which he showed the underlying mathematical similarity of the machines as force amplifiers.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Although *work* was not formally used until 1826, similar concepts existed before then.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Early names for the same concept included *moment of activity, quantity of action, latent live force, dynamic effect, efficiency*, and even *force*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In 1759, John Smeaton described a quantity that he called "power" "to signify the exertion of strength, gravitation, impulse, or pressure, as to produce motion".
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Smeaton continues that this quantity can be calculated if "the weight raised is multiplied by the height to which it can be raised in a given time", making this definition remarkably similar to Coriolis's.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The term *work* (or *mechanical work*), and the use of the work-energy principle in mechanics, was introduced in the late 1820s independently by French mathematician Gaspard-Gustave Coriolis and French Professor of Applied Mechanics Jean-Victor Poncelet.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Both scientists were pursuing a view of mechanics suitable for studying the dynamics and power of machines, for example steam engines lifting buckets of water out of flooded ore mines.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] According to Rene Dugas, French engineer and historian, it is to Solomon of Caux "that we owe the term *work* in the sense that it is used in mechanics now".
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The concept of virtual work, and the use of variational methods in mechanics, preceded the introduction of "mechanical work" but was originally called "virtual moment".
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] It was re-named once the terminology of Poncelet and Coriolis was adopted.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The SI unit of work is the joule (J), named after English physicist James Prescott Joule (1818–1889).
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The dimensionally equivalent newton-metre (N⋅m) is sometimes used as the measuring unit for work, but this can be confused with the measurement unit of torque.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Usage of N⋅m is discouraged by the SI authority, since it can lead to confusion as to whether the quantity expressed in newton-metres is a torque measurement, or a measurement of work.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Another unit for work is the foot-pound, which comes from the English system of measurement.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] As the unit name suggests, it is the product of pounds for the unit of force and feet for the unit of displacement.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] One joule is approximately equal to 0.7376 ft-lbs.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Non-SI units of work include the erg, the foot-pound, the foot-poundal, the kilowatt hour, the litre-atmosphere, and the horsepower-hour.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Due to work having the same physical dimension as heat, occasionally measurement units typically reserved for heat or energy content, such as therm, BTU and calorie, are used as a measuring unit.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] For example, if a force of 10 newtons (*F* = 10 N) acts along a point that travels 2 metres (*s* = 2 m), then *W* = *Fs* = (10 N) (2 m) = 20 J.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This is approximately the work done lifting a 1 kg object from ground level to over a person's head against the force of gravity.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work is doubled either by lifting twice the weight the same distance or by lifting the same weight twice the distance.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Energy shares the same unit of measurement with work (Joules) because the energy from the object doing work is transferred to the other objects it interacts with when work is being done.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work–energy principle states that an increase in the kinetic energy of a rigid body is caused by an equal amount of positive work done by the resultant force acting upon it.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Conversely, a decrease in kinetic energy is caused by an equal amount of negative work done by the resultant force.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Thus, if the net work is positive, then the particle's kinetic energy increases by the amount of the work.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] If the net work is negative, then the particle's kinetic energy decreases by the amount of work.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work/energy principles discussed here are identical to electric work/energy principles.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Constraint forces determine the object's displacement in the system, limiting it within a range.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] For example, in the case of a slope plus gravity, the object is *stuck to* the slope and, when attached to a taut string, it cannot move in an outwards direction to make the string any 'tauter'.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] It eliminates all displacements in that direction, that is, the velocity in the direction of the constraint is limited to 0, so that the constraint forces do not perform work on the system.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] For a mechanical system, constraint forces eliminate movement in directions that characterize the constraint.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Thus the virtual work done by the forces of constraint is zero, a result which is only true if friction forces are excluded.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Fixed, frictionless constraint forces do not perform work on the system, as the angle between the motion and the constraint forces is always 90°.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Examples of workless constraints are: rigid interconnections between particles, sliding motion on a frictionless surface, and rolling contact without slipping.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] For example, in a pulley system like the Atwood machine, the internal forces on the rope and at the supporting pulley do no work on the system.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Therefore, work need only be computed for the gravitational forces acting on the bodies.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Another example is the centripetal force exerted *inwards* by a string on a ball in uniform circular motion *sideways* constrains the ball to circular motion restricting its movement away from the centre of the circle.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This force does zero work because it is perpendicular to the velocity of the ball.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The magnetic force on a charged particle is **F** = *q***v** × **B**, where q is the charge, **v** is the velocity of the particle, and **B** is the magnetic field.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The result of a cross product is always perpendicular to both of the original vectors, so **F** ⊥ **v**.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The dot product of two perpendicular vectors is always zero, so the work *W* = **F** ⋅ **v** = 0, and the magnetic force does not do work.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] It can change the direction of motion but never change the speed.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] For moving objects, the quantity of work/time (power) is integrated along the trajectory of the point of application of the force.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Thus, at any instant, the rate of the work done by a force (measured in joules/second, or watts) is the scalar product of the force (a vector), and the velocity vector of the point of application.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This scalar product of force and velocity is known as instantaneous power.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Just as velocities may be integrated over time to obtain a total distance, by the fundamental theorem of calculus, the total work along a path is similarly the time-integral of instantaneous power applied along the trajectory of the point of application.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Work is the result of a force on a point that follows a curve **X**, with a velocity **v**, at each instant.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The small amount of work *δW* that occurs over an instant of time *dt* is calculated as $\delta W=\mathbf {F} \cdot d\mathbf {s} =\mathbf {F} \cdot \mathbf {v} dt$ where the **F** ⋅ **v** is the power over the instant *dt*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This integral is computed along the trajectory of the particle, and is therefore said to be *path dependent*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] If the force is always directed along this line, and the magnitude of the force is *F*, then this integral simplifies to $W=\int _{C}F\,ds$ where s is displacement along the line.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] If **F** is constant, in addition to being directed along the line, then the integral simplifies further to $W=\int _{C}F\,ds=F\int _{C}ds=Fs$ where *s* is the displacement of the point along the line.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This calculation can be generalized for a constant force that is not directed along the line, followed by the particle.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] When a force component is perpendicular to the displacement of the object (such as when a body moves in a circular path under a central force), no work is done, since the cosine of 90° is zero.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Thus, no work can be performed by gravity on a planet with a circular orbit (this is ideal, as all orbits are slightly elliptical).
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Also, no work is done on a body moving circularly at a constant speed while constrained by mechanical force, such as moving at constant speed in a frictionless ideal centrifuge.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Calculating the work as "force times straight path segment" would only apply in the most simple of circumstances, as noted above.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This component of force can be described by the scalar quantity called *scalar tangential component* (*F* cos(*θ*), where θ is the angle between the force and the velocity).
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Work done by a variable force is the line integral of its scalar tangential component along the path of its application point.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] If the force varies (e.g. compressing a spring) we need to use calculus to find the work done.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Thus, the work done for a variable force can be expressed as a definite integral of force over displacement.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Thus, the work done for a variable force can be expressed as a definite integral of power over time.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] A force couple results from equal and opposite forces, acting on two different points of a rigid body.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The sum (resultant) of these forces may cancel, but their effect on the body is the couple or torque **T**.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work of the torque is calculated as $\delta W=\mathbf {T} \cdot {\boldsymbol {\omega }}\,dt,$ where the **T** ⋅ ***ω*** is the power over the instant *dt*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] If the angular velocity vector maintains a constant direction, then it takes the form, ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}={\dot {\phi }}\mathbf {S} ,$ where $\phi$ is the angle of rotation about the constant unit vector **S**.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This integral depends on the rotational trajectory $\phi (t)$ , and is therefore path-dependent.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This result can be understood more simply by considering the torque as arising from a force of constant magnitude *F*, being applied perpendicularly to a lever arm at a distance r , as shown in the figure.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This force will act through the distance along the circular arc $l=s=r\phi$ , so the work done is $W=Fs=Fr\phi .$ Introduce the torque *τ* = *Fr*, to obtain $W=Fr\phi =\tau \phi ,$ as presented above.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Notice that only the component of torque in the direction of the angular velocity vector contributes to the work.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The scalar product of a force **F** and the velocity **v** of its point of application defines the power input to a system at an instant of time.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Integration of this power over the trajectory of the point of application, *C* = **x**(*t*), defines the work input to the system by the force.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In general this integral requires that the path along which the velocity is defined, so the evaluation of work is said to be path dependent.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] If the work for an applied force is independent of the path, then the work done by the force, by the gradient theorem, defines a potential function which is evaluated at the start and end of the trajectory of the point of application.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This means that there is a potential function *U*(**x**), that can be evaluated at the two points **x**(*t*1) and **x**(*t*2) to obtain the work over any trajectory between these two points.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The function *U*(**x**) is called the potential energy associated with the applied force.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The force derived from such a potential function is said to be conservative.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Examples of forces that have potential energies are gravity and spring forces.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Because the potential U defines a force **F** at every point **x** in space, the set of forces is called a force field.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In the absence of other forces, gravity results in a constant downward acceleration of every freely moving object.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Near Earth's surface the acceleration due to gravity is *g* = 9.8 m⋅s−2 and the gravitational force on an object of mass *m* is **F**g = *m***g**.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] It is convenient to imagine this gravitational force concentrated at the center of mass of the object.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] where *Fg* is weight (pound-force in imperial units, and newtons in SI units), and Δ*y* is the change in height *y*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Notice that the work done by gravity depends only on the vertical movement of the object.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The presence of friction does not affect the work done on the object by its weight.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] where **r** is the position vector from M to m and **r̂** is the unit vector in the direction of **r**.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] is the gravitational potential function, also known as gravitational potential energy.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The negative sign follows the convention that work is gained from a loss of potential energy.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Consider a spring that exerts a horizontal force **F** = (−*kx*, 0, 0) that is proportional to its deflection in the *x* direction independent of how a body moves.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work is the product of the distance times the spring force, which is also dependent on distance; hence the *x*2 result.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] where P is pressure, V is volume, and a and b are initial and final volumes.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] where $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ are the speeds of the particle before and after the work is done, and m is its mass.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The derivation of the *work–energy principle* begins with Newton's second law of motion and the resultant force on a particle.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Computation of the scalar product of the force with the velocity of the particle evaluates the instantaneous power added to the system.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] (Constraints define the direction of movement of the particle by ensuring there is no component of velocity in the direction of the constraint force.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This also means the constraint forces do not add to the instantaneous power.) The time integral of this scalar equation yields work from the instantaneous power, and kinetic energy from the scalar product of acceleration with velocity.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The fact that the work–energy principle eliminates the constraint forces underlies Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This section focuses on the work–energy principle as it applies to particle dynamics.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In more general systems work can change the potential energy of a mechanical device, the thermal energy in a thermal system, or the electrical energy in an electrical device.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Work transfers energy from one place to another or one form to another.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In the case the resultant force **F** is constant in both magnitude and direction, and parallel to the velocity of the particle, the particle is moving with constant acceleration a along a straight line.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work of the net force is calculated as the product of its magnitude and the particle displacement.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] For any net force acting on a particle moving along any curvilinear path, it can be demonstrated that its work equals the change in the kinetic energy of the particle by a simple derivation analogous to the equation above.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The remaining part of the above derivation is just simple calculus, same as in the preceding rectilinear case.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In particle dynamics, a formula equating work applied to a system to its change in kinetic energy is obtained as a first integral of Newton's second law of motion.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] It is useful to notice that the resultant force used in Newton's laws can be separated into forces that are applied to the particle and forces imposed by constraints on the movement of the particle.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Remarkably, the work of a constraint force is zero, therefore only the work of the applied forces need be considered in the work–energy principle.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] To see this, consider a particle P that follows the trajectory **X**(*t*) with a force **F** acting on it.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Note that n dots above a vector indicates its nth time derivative.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] because the constraint forces are perpendicular to the particle velocity.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The left side of this equation is the work of the applied force as it acts on the particle along the trajectory from time *t*1 to time *t*2.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This integral is computed along the trajectory **X**(*t*) of the particle and is therefore path dependent.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This derivation can be generalized to arbitrary rigid body systems.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Consider the case of a vehicle moving along a straight horizontal trajectory under the action of a driving force and gravity that sum to **F**.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] As an example consider a car skidding to a stop, where *k* is the coefficient of friction and *w* is the weight of the car.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Then the force along the trajectory is *F*x = −*kw*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This formula uses the fact that the mass of the vehicle is *m* = *w*/*g*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Consider the case of a vehicle that starts at rest and coasts down an inclined surface (such as mountain road), the work–energy principle helps compute the minimum distance that the vehicle travels to reach a velocity V, of say 60 mph (27 m/s).
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Rolling resistance and air drag will slow the vehicle down so the actual distance will be greater than if these forces are neglected.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Let the trajectory of the vehicle following the road be **X**(*t*) which is a curve in three-dimensional space.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The force acting on the vehicle that pushes it down the road is the constant force of gravity **F** = (0, 0, *w*), while the force of the road on the vehicle is the constraint force **R**.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The constraint forces between the vehicle and the road cancel from this equation because **R** ⋅ **V** = 0, which means they do no work.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] Notice that this result does not depend on the shape of the road followed by the vehicle.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] In order to determine the distance along the road assume the downgrade is 6%, which is a steep road.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This means the altitude decreases 6 feet for every 100 feet traveled—for angles this small the sin and tan functions are approximately equal.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This formula uses the fact that the weight of the vehicle is *w* = *mg*.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated from the work of a resultant force and torque.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] The trajectories of **X***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] This movement is given by the set of rotations [*A*(*t*)] and the trajectory **d**(*t*) of a reference point in the body.
[src:work-output/mechanical-work] where **F** and **T** are the resultant force and torque applied at the reference point **d** of the moving frame M in the rigid body.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics is one of the oldest academic disciplines.
[src:work-output/physics] Over much of the past two millennia, physics, chemistry, biology, and certain branches of mathematics were part of natural philosophy, but during the Scientific Revolution in the 17th century, these natural sciences branched into separate research endeavors.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics intersects with many interdisciplinary areas of research, such as biophysics and quantum chemistry, and the boundaries of physics are not rigidly defined.
[src:work-output/physics] New ideas in physics often explain the fundamental mechanisms studied by other sciences and suggest new avenues of research in these and other academic disciplines, such as mathematics and philosophy.
[src:work-output/physics] Advances in physics often enable new technologies.
[src:work-output/physics] The word *physics* comes from the Latin *physica* ('study of nature'), which itself is a borrowing of the Greek φυσική (*phusikḗ* 'natural science'), a term derived from φύσις (*phúsis* 'origin, nature, property').
[src:work-output/physics] Astronomy is one of the oldest natural sciences.
[src:work-output/physics] Early civilizations dating before 3000 BCE, such as the Sumerians, ancient Egyptians, and the Indus Valley Civilization, had a predictive knowledge and a basic awareness of the motions of the Sun, Moon, and stars.
[src:work-output/physics] The stars and planets, believed to represent gods, were often worshipped.
[src:work-output/physics] While the explanations for the observed positions of the stars were often unscientific and lacking in evidence, these early observations laid the foundation for later astronomy, as the stars were found to traverse great circles across the sky, which could not explain the positions of the planets.
[src:work-output/physics] According to Asger Aaboe, the origins of Western astronomy can be found in Mesopotamia, and all Western efforts in the exact sciences are descended from late Babylonian astronomy.
[src:work-output/physics] Natural philosophy has its origins in Greece during the Archaic period (650 BCE – 480 BCE), when pre-Socratic philosophers like Thales rejected non-naturalistic explanations for natural phenomena and proclaimed that every event had a natural cause.
[src:work-output/physics] They proposed ideas verified by reason and observation, and many of their hypotheses proved successful in experiment; for example, atomism was found to be correct approximately 2000 years after it was proposed by Leucippus and his pupil Democritus.
[src:work-output/physics] During the classical period in Greece (6th, 5th and 4th centuries BCE) and in Hellenistic times, natural philosophy developed along many lines of inquiry.
[src:work-output/physics] Aristotle (Greek: Ἀριστοτέλης, *Aristotélēs*) (384–322 BCE), a student of Plato, wrote on many subjects, including a substantial treatise on "Physics" – in the 4th century BC.
[src:work-output/physics] Aristotelian physics was influential for about two millennia.
[src:work-output/physics] His approach mixed some limited observation with logical deductive arguments, but did not rely on experimental verification of deduced statements.
[src:work-output/physics] Aristotle's foundational work in Physics, though very imperfect, formed a framework against which later thinkers further developed the field.
[src:work-output/physics] His approach is entirely superseded today.
[src:work-output/physics] He explained ideas such as motion (and gravity) with the theory of four elements.
[src:work-output/physics] Aristotle believed that each of the four classical elements (air, fire, water, earth) had its own natural place.
[src:work-output/physics] Because of their differing densities, each element will revert to its own specific place in the atmosphere.
[src:work-output/physics] So, because of their weights, fire would be at the top, air underneath fire, then water, then lastly earth.
[src:work-output/physics] He also stated that when a small amount of one element enters the natural place of another, the less abundant element will automatically go towards its own natural place.
[src:work-output/physics] For example, if there is a fire on the ground, the flames go up into the air in an attempt to go back into its natural place where it belongs.
[src:work-output/physics] His laws of motion included: that heavier objects will fall faster, the speed being proportional to the weight and the speed of the object that is falling depends inversely on the density object it is falling through (e.g. density of air).
[src:work-output/physics] He also stated that, when it comes to violent motion (motion of an object when a force is applied to it by a second object), the speed that object moves will only be as fast or strong as the measure of force applied to it.
[src:work-output/physics] The problem of motion and its causes was studied carefully, leading to the philosophical notion of a "prime mover" as the ultimate source of all motion in the world (Book 8 of his treatise *Physics*).
[src:work-output/physics] The Western Roman Empire fell to invaders and internal decay in the fifth century, resulting in a decline in intellectual pursuits in western Europe.
[src:work-output/physics] By contrast, the Eastern Roman Empire (usually known as the Byzantine Empire) resisted the attacks from invaders and continued to advance various fields of learning, including physics.
[src:work-output/physics] In the sixth century, John Philoponus challenged the dominant Aristotelian approach to science although much of his work was focused on Christian theology.
[src:work-output/physics] In the sixth century, Isidore of Miletus created an important compilation of Archimedes' works that are copied in the Archimedes Palimpsest.
[src:work-output/physics] Islamic scholarship inherited Aristotelian physics from the Greeks and during the Islamic Golden Age developed it further.
[src:work-output/physics] The most notable innovations under Islamic scholarship were in the field of optics and vision, which came from the works of many scientists like Ibn Sahl, Al-Kindi, Ibn al-Haytham, Al-Farisi and Avicenna.
[src:work-output/physics] In his Book of Optics (also known as Kitāb al-Manāẓir) Ibn al-Haytham presented the idea of light rays as an alternative to the ancient Greek idea about visual rays.
[src:work-output/physics] Like Ptolemy, Ibn al-Haytham applied controlled experiments, verifying the laws of refraction and reflection with the new concept of light rays, but still lacking the concept of image formation.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics became a separate science when early modern Europeans used experimental and quantitative methods to discover what are now considered to be the laws of physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Newton, and separately Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, developed calculus, the mathematical study of continuous change, and Newton applied it to solve physical problems.
[src:work-output/physics] The discovery of laws in thermodynamics, chemistry, and electromagnetics resulted from research efforts during the Industrial Revolution as energy needs increased.
[src:work-output/physics] By the end of the 19th century, theories of thermodynamics, mechanics, and electromagnetics matched a wide variety of observations.
[src:work-output/physics] Taken together these theories became the basis for what would later be called classical physics.
[src:work-output/physics] A few experimental results remained inexplicable.
[src:work-output/physics] Classical electromagnetism presumed a medium, an luminiferous aether to support the propagation of waves, but this medium could not be detected.
[src:work-output/physics] The intensity of light from hot glowing blackbody objects did not match the predictions of thermodynamics and electromagnetism.
[src:work-output/physics] The character of electron emission of illuminated metals differed from predictions.
[src:work-output/physics] These failures, seemingly insignificant in the big picture would upset the physics world in first two decades of the 20th century.
[src:work-output/physics] Modern physics began in the early 20th century with the work of Max Planck in quantum theory and Albert Einstein's theory of relativity.
[src:work-output/physics] Both of these theories came about due to inaccuracies in classical mechanics in certain situations.
[src:work-output/physics] Classical mechanics predicted that the speed of light depends on the motion of the observer, which could not be resolved with the constant speed predicted by Maxwell's equations of electromagnetism.
[src:work-output/physics] This discrepancy was corrected by Einstein's theory of special relativity, which replaced classical mechanics for fast-moving bodies and allowed for a constant speed of light.
[src:work-output/physics] Black-body radiation provided another problem for classical physics, which was corrected when Planck proposed that the excitation of material oscillators is possible only in discrete steps proportional to their frequency.
[src:work-output/physics] This, along with the photoelectric effect and a complete theory predicting discrete energy levels of electron orbitals, led to the theory of quantum mechanics improving on classical physics at very small scales.
[src:work-output/physics] Quantum mechanics would come to be pioneered by Werner Heisenberg, Erwin Schrödinger and Paul Dirac.
[src:work-output/physics] From this early work, and work in related fields, the Standard Model of particle physics was derived.
[src:work-output/physics] Areas of mathematics in general are important to this field, such as the study of probabilities and groups.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics deals with a wide variety of systems, although certain theories are used by all physicists.
[src:work-output/physics] Each of these theories was experimentally tested numerous times and found to be an adequate approximation of nature.
[src:work-output/physics] These central theories are important tools for research into more specialized topics, and any physicist, regardless of their specialization, is expected to be literate in them.
[src:work-output/physics] These include classical mechanics, quantum mechanics, thermodynamics and statistical mechanics, electromagnetism, and special relativity.
[src:work-output/physics] In the first decades of the 20th century physics was revolutionized by the discoveries of quantum mechanics and relativity.
[src:work-output/physics] The changes were so fundamental that these new concepts became the foundation of "modern physics", with other topics becoming "classical physics".
[src:work-output/physics] The majority of applications of physics are essentially classical.
[src:work-output/physics] The laws of classical physics accurately describe systems whose important length scales are greater than the atomic scale and whose motions are much slower than the speed of light.
[src:work-output/physics] Outside of this domain, observations do not match predictions provided by classical mechanics.
[src:work-output/physics] Classical physics includes the traditional branches and topics that were recognized and well-developed before the beginning of the 20th century—classical mechanics, thermodynamics, and electromagnetism.
[src:work-output/physics] Acoustics is the study of how sound is produced, controlled, transmitted and received.
[src:work-output/physics] Important modern branches of acoustics include ultrasonics, the study of sound waves of very high frequency beyond the range of human hearing; bioacoustics, the physics of animal calls and hearing; and electroacoustics, the manipulation of audible sound waves using electronics.
[src:work-output/physics] Optics, the study of light, is concerned not only with visible light but also with infrared and ultraviolet radiation, which exhibit all of the phenomena of visible light except visibility, e.g., reflection, refraction, interference, diffraction, dispersion, and polarization of light.
[src:work-output/physics] Heat is a form of energy, the internal energy possessed by the particles of which a substance is composed; thermodynamics deals with the relationships between heat and other forms of energy.
[src:work-output/physics] Electricity and magnetism have been studied as a single branch of physics since the intimate connection between them was discovered in the early 19th century; an electric current gives rise to a magnetic field, and a changing magnetic field induces an electric current.
[src:work-output/physics] Electrostatics deals with electric charges at rest, electrodynamics with moving charges, and magnetostatics with magnetic poles at rest.
[src:work-output/physics] The discovery of relativity and of quantum mechanics in the first decades of the 20th century transformed the conceptual basis of physics without reducing the practical value of most of the physical theories developed up to that time.
[src:work-output/physics] Consequently the topics of physics have come to be divided into "classical physics" and "modern physics", with the latter category including effects related to quantum mechanics and relativity.
[src:work-output/physics] Classical physics is generally concerned with matter and energy on the normal scale of observation, while much of modern physics is concerned with the behavior of matter and energy under extreme conditions or on a very large or very small scale.
[src:work-output/physics] For example, atomic and nuclear physics study matter on the smallest scale at which chemical elements can be identified.
[src:work-output/physics] The physics of elementary particles is on an even smaller scale since it is concerned with the most basic units of matter; this branch of physics is also known as high-energy physics because of the extremely high energies necessary to produce many types of particles in particle accelerators.
[src:work-output/physics] On this scale, ordinary, commonsensical notions of space, time, matter, and energy are no longer valid.
[src:work-output/physics] The two chief theories of modern physics present a different picture of the concepts of space, time, and matter from that presented by classical physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Classical mechanics approximates nature as continuous, while quantum theory is concerned with the discrete nature of many phenomena at the atomic and subatomic level and with the complementary aspects of particles and waves in the description of such phenomena.
[src:work-output/physics] Both quantum theory and the theory of relativity find applications in many areas of modern physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Physicists use the scientific method to test the validity of a physical theory.
[src:work-output/physics] By using a methodical approach to compare the implications of a theory with the conclusions drawn from its related experiments and observations, physicists are better able to test the validity of a theory in a logical, unbiased, and repeatable way.
[src:work-output/physics] To that end, experiments are performed and observations are made in order to determine the validity or invalidity of a theory.
[src:work-output/physics] A scientific law is a concise verbal or mathematical statement of a relation that expresses a fundamental principle of some theory, such as Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:work-output/physics] Theorists seek to develop mathematical models that both agree with existing experiments and successfully predict future experimental results, while experimentalists devise and perform experiments to test theoretical predictions and explore new phenomena.
[src:work-output/physics] Although theory and experiment are developed separately, they strongly affect and depend upon each other.
[src:work-output/physics] Physicists who work at the interplay of theory and experiment are called phenomenologists, who study complex phenomena observed in experiment and work to relate them to a fundamental theory.
[src:work-output/physics] Theoretical physics has historically taken inspiration from philosophy; electromagnetism was unified this way.
[src:work-output/physics] Beyond the known universe, the field of theoretical physics also deals with hypothetical issues, such as parallel universes, a multiverse, and higher dimensions.
[src:work-output/physics] Theorists invoke these ideas in hopes of solving particular problems with existing theories; they then explore the consequences of these ideas and work toward making testable predictions.
[src:work-output/physics] Experimental physics expands, and is expanded by, engineering and technology.
[src:work-output/physics] Experimental physicists who are involved in basic research design and perform experiments with equipment such as particle accelerators and lasers, whereas those involved in applied research often work in industry, developing technologies such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and transistors.
[src:work-output/physics] Feynman has noted that experimentalists may seek areas that have not been explored well by theorists.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics covers a wide range of phenomena, from elementary particles (such as quarks, neutrinos, and electrons) to the largest superclusters of galaxies.
[src:work-output/physics] Included in these phenomena are the most basic objects composing all other things.
[src:work-output/physics] Therefore, physics is sometimes called the "fundamental science".
[src:work-output/physics] Physics aims to describe the various phenomena that occur in nature in terms of simpler phenomena.
[src:work-output/physics] Thus, physics aims to both connect the things observable to humans to root causes, and then connect these causes together.
[src:work-output/physics] For example, the ancient Chinese observed that certain rocks (lodestone and magnetite) were attracted to one another by an invisible force.
[src:work-output/physics] This effect was later called magnetism, which was first rigorously studied in the 17th century.
[src:work-output/physics] But even before the Chinese discovered magnetism, the ancient Greeks knew of other objects such as amber, that when rubbed with fur would cause a similar invisible attraction between the two.
[src:work-output/physics] This was also first studied rigorously in the 17th century and came to be called electricity.
[src:work-output/physics] Thus, physics had come to understand two observations of nature in terms of some root cause (electricity and magnetism).
[src:work-output/physics] However, further work in the 19th century revealed that these two forces were just two different aspects of one force—electromagnetism.
[src:work-output/physics] This process of "unifying" forces continues today, and electromagnetism and the weak nuclear force are now considered to be two aspects of the electroweak interaction.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics hopes to find an ultimate reason (theory of everything) for why nature is as it is (see section *Current research* below for more information).
[src:work-output/physics] Research in physics is continually progressing on a large number of fronts.
[src:work-output/physics] In condensed matter physics, an important unsolved theoretical problem is that of high-temperature superconductivity.
[src:work-output/physics] Many condensed matter experiments are aiming to fabricate workable spintronics and quantum computers.
[src:work-output/physics] In particle physics, the first pieces of experimental evidence for physics beyond the Standard Model have begun to appear.
[src:work-output/physics] Foremost among these are indications that neutrinos have non-zero mass.
[src:work-output/physics] These experimental results appear to have solved the long-standing solar neutrino problem, and the physics of massive neutrinos remains an area of active theoretical and experimental research.
[src:work-output/physics] The Large Hadron Collider has already found the Higgs boson, but future research aims to prove or disprove the supersymmetry, which extends the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Research on the nature of the major mysteries of dark matter and dark energy is also currently ongoing.
[src:work-output/physics] Although much progress has been made in high-energy, quantum, and astronomical physics, many everyday phenomena involving complexity, chaos, or turbulence are still poorly understood.
[src:work-output/physics] These complex phenomena have received growing attention since the 1970s for several reasons, including the availability of modern mathematical methods and computers, which enabled complex systems to be modeled in new ways.
[src:work-output/physics] Complex physics has become part of increasingly interdisciplinary research, as exemplified by the study of turbulence in aerodynamics and the observation of pattern formation in biological systems.
[src:work-output/physics] The major fields of physics, along with their subfields and the theories and concepts they employ, are shown in the following table.
[src:work-output/physics] Since the 20th century, the individual fields of physics have become increasingly specialized, and today most physicists work in a single field for their entire careers.
[src:work-output/physics] "Universalists" such as Einstein (1879–1955) and Lev Landau (1908–1968), who worked in multiple fields of physics, are now very rare.
[src:work-output/physics] Contemporary research in physics can be broadly divided into nuclear and particle physics; condensed matter physics; atomic, molecular, and optical physics; astrophysics; and applied physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Some physics departments also support physics education research and physics outreach.
[src:work-output/physics] Particle physics is the study of the elementary constituents of matter and energy and the interactions between them.
[src:work-output/physics] In addition, particle physicists design and develop the high-energy accelerators, detectors, and computer programs necessary for this research.
[src:work-output/physics] The field is also called "high-energy physics" because many elementary particles do not occur naturally but are created only during high-energy collisions of other particles.
[src:work-output/physics] Currently, the interactions of elementary particles and fields are described by the Standard Model.
[src:work-output/physics] The model accounts for the 12 known particles of matter (quarks and leptons) that interact via the strong, weak, and electromagnetic fundamental forces.
[src:work-output/physics] Dynamics are described in terms of matter particles exchanging gauge bosons (gluons, W and Z bosons, and photons, respectively).
[src:work-output/physics] The Standard Model also predicts a particle known as the Higgs boson.
[src:work-output/physics] In July 2012 CERN, the European laboratory for particle physics, announced the detection of a particle consistent with the Higgs boson, an integral part of the Higgs mechanism.
[src:work-output/physics] Nuclear physics is the field of physics that studies the constituents and interactions of atomic nuclei.
[src:work-output/physics] Atomic, molecular, and optical physics (AMO) is the study of matter—matter and light—matter interactions on the scale of single atoms and molecules.
[src:work-output/physics] The three areas are grouped together because of their interrelationships, the similarity of methods used, and the commonality of their relevant energy scales.
[src:work-output/physics] All three areas include both classical, semi-classical and quantum treatments; they can treat their subject from a microscopic view (in contrast to a macroscopic view).
[src:work-output/physics] Atomic physics studies the electron shells of atoms.
[src:work-output/physics] Current research focuses on activities in quantum control, cooling and trapping of atoms and ions, low-temperature collision dynamics and the effects of electron correlation on structure and dynamics.
[src:work-output/physics] Atomic physics is influenced by the nucleus (see hyperfine splitting), but intra-nuclear phenomena such as fission and fusion are considered part of nuclear physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Molecular physics focuses on multi-atomic structures and their internal and external interactions with matter and light.
[src:work-output/physics] Optical physics is distinct from optics in that it tends to focus not on the control of classical light fields by macroscopic objects but on the fundamental properties of optical fields and their interactions with matter in the microscopic realm.
[src:work-output/physics] Condensed matter physics is the field of physics that deals with the macroscopic physical properties of matter.
[src:work-output/physics] In particular, it is concerned with the "condensed" phases that appear whenever the number of particles in a system is extremely large and the interactions between them are strong.
[src:work-output/physics] The most familiar examples of condensed phases are solids and liquids, which arise from the bonding by way of the electromagnetic force between atoms.
[src:work-output/physics] Condensed matter physics is the largest field of contemporary physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Historically, condensed matter physics grew out of solid-state physics, which is now considered one of its main subfields.
[src:work-output/physics] The term *condensed matter physics* was apparently coined by Philip Anderson when he renamed his research group—previously *solid-state theory*—in 1967.
[src:work-output/physics] In 1978, the Division of Solid State Physics of the American Physical Society was renamed as the Division of Condensed Matter Physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Condensed matter physics has a large overlap with chemistry, materials science, nanotechnology and engineering.
[src:work-output/physics] Astrophysics and astronomy are the application of the theories and methods of physics to the study of stellar structure, stellar evolution, the origin of the Solar System, and related problems of cosmology.
[src:work-output/physics] Because astrophysics is a broad subject, astrophysicists typically apply many disciplines of physics, including mechanics, electromagnetism, statistical mechanics, thermodynamics, quantum mechanics, relativity, nuclear and particle physics, and atomic and molecular physics.
[src:work-output/physics] The discovery by Karl Jansky in 1931 that radio signals were emitted by celestial bodies initiated the science of radio astronomy.
[src:work-output/physics] Most recently, the frontiers of astronomy have been expanded by space exploration.
[src:work-output/physics] Perturbations and interference from the Earth's atmosphere make space-based observations necessary for infrared, ultraviolet, gamma-ray, and X-ray astronomy.
[src:work-output/physics] Physical cosmology is the study of the formation and evolution of the universe on its largest scales.
[src:work-output/physics] Albert Einstein's theory of relativity plays a central role in all modern cosmological theories.
[src:work-output/physics] In the early 20th century, Hubble's discovery that the universe is expanding, as shown by the Hubble diagram, prompted rival explanations known as the steady state universe and the Big Bang.
[src:work-output/physics] The Big Bang was confirmed by the success of Big Bang nucleosynthesis and the discovery of the cosmic microwave background in 1964.
[src:work-output/physics] The Big Bang model rests on two theoretical pillars: Albert Einstein's general relativity and the cosmological principle.
[src:work-output/physics] Cosmologists have recently established the ΛCDM model of the evolution of the universe, which includes cosmic inflation, dark energy, and dark matter.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics education or physics teaching refers to the education methods currently used to teach physics.
[src:work-output/physics] The occupation is called physics educator or physics teacher.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics education research refers to an area of pedagogical research that seeks to improve those methods.
[src:work-output/physics] Historically, physics has been taught at the high school and college level primarily by the lecture method together with laboratory exercises aimed at verifying concepts taught in the lectures.
[src:work-output/physics] These concepts are better understood when lectures are accompanied with demonstration, hand-on experiments, and questions that require students to ponder what will happen in an experiment and why.
[src:work-output/physics] Students who participate in active learning for example with hands-on experiments learn through self-discovery.
[src:work-output/physics] By trial and error they learn to change their preconceptions about phenomena in physics and discover the underlying concepts.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics education is part of the broader area of science education.
[src:work-output/physics] A physicist is a scientist who specializes in the field of physics, which encompasses the interactions of matter and energy at all length and time scales in the physical universe.
[src:work-output/physics] Physicists generally are interested in the root or ultimate causes of phenomena, and usually frame their understanding in mathematical terms.
[src:work-output/physics] They work across a wide range of research fields, spanning all length scales: from sub-atomic and particle physics, through biological physics, to cosmological length scales encompassing the universe as a whole.
[src:work-output/physics] Physicists can apply their knowledge towards solving practical problems or to developing new technologies (also known as applied physics or engineering physics).
[src:work-output/physics] Physics, as with the rest of science, relies on the philosophy of science and its "scientific method" to advance knowledge of the physical world.
[src:work-output/physics] The scientific method employs *a priori and a posteriori* reasoning as well as the use of Bayesian inference to measure the validity of a given theory.
[src:work-output/physics] Study of the philosophical issues surrounding physics, the philosophy of physics, involves issues such as the nature of space and time, determinism, and metaphysical outlooks such as empiricism, naturalism, and realism.
[src:work-output/physics] Many physicists have written about the philosophical implications of their work, for instance Laplace, who championed causal determinism, and Erwin Schrödinger, who wrote on quantum mechanics.
[src:work-output/physics] The mathematical physicist Roger Penrose has been called a Platonist by Stephen Hawking, a view Penrose discusses in his book, *The Road to Reality*.
[src:work-output/physics] Hawking referred to himself as an "unashamed reductionist" and took issue with Penrose's views.
[src:work-output/physics] Mathematics provides a compact and exact language used to describe the order in nature.
[src:work-output/physics] This was noted and advocated by Pythagoras, Plato, Galileo, and Newton.
[src:work-output/physics] Some theorists, like Hilary Putnam and Penelope Maddy, hold that logical truths, and therefore mathematical reasoning, depend on the empirical world.
[src:work-output/physics] This is usually combined with the claim that the laws of logic express universal regularities found in the structural features of the world, which may explain the peculiar relation between these fields.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics uses mathematics to organize and formulate experimental results.
[src:work-output/physics] From those results, precise or estimated solutions are obtained, or quantitative results, from which new predictions can be made and experimentally confirmed or negated.
[src:work-output/physics] The results from physics experiments are numerical data, with their units of measure and estimates of the errors in the measurements.
[src:work-output/physics] Technologies based on mathematics, like computation have made computational physics an active area of research.
[src:work-output/physics] Ontology is a prerequisite for physics, but not for mathematics.
[src:work-output/physics] It means physics is ultimately concerned with descriptions of the real world, while mathematics is concerned with abstract patterns, even beyond the real world.
[src:work-output/physics] Thus physics statements are synthetic, while mathematical statements are analytic.
[src:work-output/physics] Mathematics contains hypotheses, while physics contains theories.
[src:work-output/physics] Mathematics statements have to be only logically true, while predictions of physics statements must match observed and experimental data.
[src:work-output/physics] The distinction is clear-cut, but not always obvious.
[src:work-output/physics] For example, mathematical physics is the application of mathematics in physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Its methods are mathematical, but its subject is physical.
[src:work-output/physics] The problems in this field start with a "mathematical model of a physical situation" (system) and a "mathematical description of a physical law" that will be applied to that system.
[src:work-output/physics] Every mathematical statement used for solving has a hard-to-find physical meaning.
[src:work-output/physics] The final mathematical solution has an easier-to-find meaning, because it is what the solver is looking for.
[src:work-output/physics] Physics is a branch of fundamental science (also called basic science).
[src:work-output/physics] Physics is also called "*the* fundamental science" because all branches of natural science including chemistry, astronomy, geology, and biology are constrained by laws of physics.
[src:work-output/physics] Similarly, chemistry is often called the central science because of its role in linking the physical sciences.
[src:work-output/physics] For example, chemistry studies properties, structures, and reactions of matter (chemistry's focus on the molecular and atomic scale distinguishes it from physics).
[src:work-output/physics] Structures are formed because particles exert electrical forces on each other, properties include physical characteristics of given substances, and reactions are bound by laws of physics, like conservation of energy, mass, and charge.
[src:work-output/physics] Fundamental physics seeks to better explain and understand phenomena in all spheres, without a specific practical application as a goal, other than the deeper insight into the phenomema themselves.
[src:work-output/physics] Applied physics is a general term for physics research and development that is intended for a particular use.
[src:work-output/physics] An applied physics curriculum usually contains a few classes in an applied discipline, like geology or electrical engineering.
[src:work-output/physics] It usually differs from engineering in that an applied physicist may not be designing something in particular, but rather is using physics or conducting physics research with the aim of developing new technologies or solving a problem.
[src:work-output/physics] The approach is similar to that of applied mathematics.
[src:work-output/physics] Applied physicists use physics in scientific research.
[src:work-output/physics] For instance, people working on accelerator physics might seek to build better particle detectors for research in theoretical physics.
[src:work-output/physics] For example, statics, a subfield of mechanics, is used in the building of bridges and other static structures.
[src:work-output/physics] The understanding and use of acoustics results in sound control and better concert halls; similarly, the use of optics creates better optical devices.
[src:work-output/physics] An understanding of physics makes for more realistic flight simulators, video games, and movies, and is often critical in forensic investigations.
[src:work-output/physics] With the standard consensus that the laws of physics are universal and do not change with time, physics can be used to study things that would ordinarily be mired in uncertainty.
[src:work-output/physics] For example, in the study of the origin of the Earth, a physicist can reasonably model Earth's mass, temperature, and rate of rotation, as a function of time allowing the extrapolation forward or backward in time and so predict future or prior events.
[src:work-output/physics] It also allows for simulations in engineering that speed up the development of a new technology.
[src:work-output/physics] There is also considerable interdisciplinarity, so many other important fields are influenced by physics (e.g., the fields of econophysics and sociophysics).
[src:work-output/work-output] In physics, *work output* is the work done by a simple machine, compound machine, or any type of engine model.
[src:work-output/work-output] In common terms, it is the energy output, which for simple machines is always less than the energy input, even though the forces may be drastically different.
[src:work-output/work-output] In [thermodynamics], work output can refer to the thermodynamic work done by a heat engine, in which case the amount of work output must be less than the input as energy is lost to heat, as determined by the engine's efficiency.
